However, they do come with a trade-off: you have to pay a commission for each ETF trade, just like you would for a stock. Additionally, ETFs are known for their wide range of available funds. It's beneficial for investors to assess whether the claimed benefits, such as diversification, actually exist and to what degree. For this analysis, we will examine the IHF ETF and its top 10 holdings, which account for 63.58% of the total assets, to evaluate if owning a single ETF could provide benefits similar to owning a diversified portfolio of the top 10 stocks, and if there are configurations that offer better risk-return ratios. To streamline our analysis, we'll focus on the top 10 holdings. The table below lists these holdings and their respective percentages of total assets.

To gauge how well these top 10 stocks represent the IHF ETF, we will calculate their contributions to a portfolio's Beta and Return, assuming the portfolio consists of these 10 stocks in the same proportions as the ETF's holdings. The calculations for Beta and return are shown in the chart below.

From this chart, it's clear that a portfolio of just the top 10 holdings would yield a 6.11% higher return than the ETF, an increase of 16%. Additionally, the Beta of the top 10 holdings is lower by 0.12 than that of the entire ETF. Based on these results, a portfolio of the top 10 holdings could potentially offer a higher return with a lower risk (Beta). However, statistical differences between the two portfolios remain uncertain.

To further evaluate the statistical differences between the two portfolios, we will calculate the standard deviation of each of the top 10 stocks and normalize it to 100% to compare their accumulated standard deviation against that of the IHF ETF.

"Dream-Land" is one of Edgar Allan Poe's self-proclaimed best poems. In this work, Poe employs the term "Thulé" in lines 6 and 56, which Mabbott links to Virgil. Virgil used the term to refer to an island north of Britain, seen by the Greeks as the farthest known world. While Virgil indeed used the term, another more recent source may have influenced Poe. Poe was particularly interested in German authors.

The quote is notable for demonstrating Poe's familiarity with Goethe's writing. Karl J. Arndt, in "Poe's Politian and Goethe's Mignon," points out the similarities between Poe's and Goethe's poems, concluding that Poe was likely imitating Goethe.

The Oxford Companion to English Literature describes Goethe as a renowned writer of the poetic drama "Faust," published in two parts, the first in 1808 and the second in 1832, the year of Goethe's death. In the second part of Faust, there's a short poem called "The King of Thulé," about a king who loses his wife after receiving a goblet from her. Driven by grief to drink, he eventually decides to end his life and throw the goblet into the sea. The king's fate echoes the desolation and grief found in "Dream-Land."

Poe mentions Thule twice in his works, including "The Pit and the Pendulum." In "Dream-Land," he uses the term twice as bookends for the poem. "The King of Thulé" and "Dream-Land" can be seen as companion pieces. In "Dream-Land," the speaker describes the landscape of Thulé as dark and lonely, haunted by dead friends, and devoid of color—a representation of Poe's own feelings of loss and despair over drinking. The poem reads as if the speaker has stepped into Goethe's world.

Goethe was a significant author whose works Poe would have known, possibly due to his admiration for Tennyson. When asked about Tennyson, Poe expressed his admiration. Additionally, Poe would have been exposed to Goethe's work through various reproductions following the original publications.

According to California law, could a customer injured by falling on an applesauce spill in a grocery store win punitive damages by proving the store manager acted maliciously, knowing the spill was dangerous but not addressing it for half an hour to finish his dinner?

A judge is unlikely to dismiss Jennifer Palmer's claim for punitive damages outright. To win such damages, she must show the store manager's actions were deliberate and showed a disregard for the risk of harm, as well as that the actions were particularly egregious. Palmer can argue that the manager should have cleaned the spill promptly to prevent further injuries, given that multiple customers had previously slipped and fallen due to spills. While her argument that the manager's inaction was despicable may not be overwhelmingly convincing, it is still reasonable given that six slip-and-fall incidents had occurred in the store in 2009, and the manager did not take sufficient action to ensure customer safety.

On October 13, 2009, at 5:00 pm, an employee named Rich Wayne informed his manager, Paul Martin, about an applesauce spill in an aisle. Martin responded that he was on his dinner break and couldn't deal with the issue. At 5:15 pm, another employee, Mary J. Haddigan, also reported the spill to Martin, who responded similarly. At 5:30 pm, Palmer slipped and fell on the spill, sustaining a serious back injury. Before Palmer's accident, five other slip-and-fall incidents had been reported at D&D's in 2009. Palmer is now suing D&D for both compensatory and punitive damages, and we are considering whether to file a summary judgment motion against the punitive damages claim.

In California, a plaintiff can obtain punitive damages for a non-contractual breach if the defendant acted with "oppression, fraud, or malice." Cal. Civ. Code, § 3294(a) (Lexis 2010). The statute defines malice as conduct that either intended to cause harm or, if there was no such intent, was "despicable" and was done with a "willful and conscious disregard of the rights or safety of others." Id. at § (c)(1). Courts have deemed conduct malicious when the defendant was aware of the probable dangerous consequences of their actions and willfully failed to avoid them. Taylor v. Super. Ct. of Los Angeles Co., 598 P. 2d 853, 856 (Cal. 1979).

Around four years ago, I took an Islam class at CBC. Our class frequently debated whether Islam is a hostile religion, and that question seems more pertinent now than ever. Reflecting on events since 9/11, I've noticed a shift in the U.S. media's portrayal of Islam and extremists, from hostility to extreme tolerance. In 2001, it's unlikely we would have seen a presidential candidate like Barack Obama, with an evident Muslim background in his family. The Prophet Muhammad's biography intrigues me because it seems to conflict with the historical accounts of his personality. Traditionally, I believed Muhammad forced converts to Islam through conquest, but the biography portrays him as a humble prophet misunderstood by others, who one by one came to acknowledge his teachings. The similarities between Jesus' ministry and Muhammad's miracles, such as multiplying mutton and milk to feed forty men, suggest the writers aimed to depict Muhammad as a prophet who didn't need to prove his credentials but simply lived his truth. This approach, I argue, diminishes Jesus' life and miracles. Moreover, many stories in the biography seem to aim to provide 'witnesses' or personal conversions to Islam, often based on hearsay. These accounts, with their third-party perspectives, feel less credible and more suspicious to me. Lastly, I find the biography's portrayal of Muhammad as a godly, humble, wise, and gentle man misleading, as historical records show otherwise. I wonder if modern Muslims are aware of the true history behind Muhammad's rise to power.

After Jesus' passing, his teachings and beliefs were quickly overshadowed in the evolution of Christian thought. Over time, Christianity diverged increasingly from its original roots. Present-day society exhibits a heightened awareness and progressive tendencies, though traditionalists may linger and oppose new ideas. Christian historians will likely deepen their understanding of the faith, seeking to distinguish later additions from Jesus' original intentions. Eventually, a strong movement will emerge to strip away these additions, reverting Christianity to its initial form. As this trend spreads in the United States and Europe, masses may return to worshipping as they did during Jesus' time, guided by his ideas alone. Although this could lead to increased uniformity within Christianity, the institutional church will remain strong. Throughout history, we've seen reversals, such as when Christianity went from being persecuted by the Roman Empire to becoming its dominant religion. The impending reversion in Christianity will follow this pattern, simplifying the faith and reducing its diversity. This transformation will be aided by interpreting Jesus' words metaphorically rather than literally. Looking back through history, Judaism was the precursor to Christianity, centered around monotheism, divine revelation, and the authority of the Hebrew scriptures before the Romans controlled Jerusalem in 63 B.C.E. Jews were diverse, categorized into groups like Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, and Zealots, along with a majority of common people.

I contend that "The Jungle" by Upton Sinclair illustrates the inherent greed and self-interest of human nature. Individuals prioritize their own well-being and success, disregarding those beneath them. This theme is evident in the factory owners and managers, whose sole aim is to expand their empires, without regard for the harm caused by their actions. Sinclair's description of the factories "a line of buildings stood clear-cut and black against the sky, with great chimneys pouring out rivers of smoke" underscores the environmental damage they inflict. The owners' apathy towards the suffering of people and animals, whether from pollution or harsh working conditions, is apparent. They prioritize profits over worker safety, as seen in their exploitative labor practices and absence of compensation for layoffs. Laws and regulations during that time offered little protection, allowing managers and owners to exploit their employees in substandard conditions. Workers were essentially trapped in this system, with no recourse or assistance, and were often forced to work to the point of death. Unions, while formed to help, often compounded the workers' misery by enriching themselves. Sinclair's comparison of workers to slaves highlights their desperate plight, unable to escape the brutal system that left them "hanging always on the verge of starvation, dependent for opportunities of life upon the whim of men as brutal and unscrupulous as the old-time slave drivers"

Many authors employ various methods to evoke specific emotions or perspectives in their readers. F. Scott Fitzgerald, in his novel "The Great Gatsby," employs a number of these techniques with varying degrees of effectiveness. One approach he uses is to pair adjectives and nouns in unusual combinations to create a particular atmosphere. Additionally, he assigns symbolic significance to colors and reuses these symbols to reinforce his narrative. In "The Great Gatsby," Fitzgerald attributes specific meanings to colors like white/gray and red/pink, which he then employs to evoke particular sensations around key subjects.

Fitzgerald's association of white/gray with uniformity is evident in his use of these colors throughout the novel. White is often associated with higher social status and elegance, while gray signifies age and faded appearances. This is first established at the novel's outset with frequent mentions of white and gray. Characters such as Daisy and Jordan are consistently described as "in white," and even minor characters like Nick, Tom, and Catherine are depicted in white attire. Furthermore, Fitzgerald employs these colors to describe mundane subjects, enhancing their significance. For instance, Nick travels "down the white chasms of lower New York," and the names of partygoers are "gray names." Even simple objects and settings, like apartment houses and cars, are described in terms of white and gray, reinforcing their symbolism.

After establishing the meanings of white/gray, Fitzgerald uses them to convey a sense of uniformity or insignificance. This technique begins with Daisy, who is first described as "dressed in white" in a "little white roadster." This use of white diminishes her character status, making her seem more like a uniform addition, an object of Gatsby's desire. Fitzgerald continues to use this technique with Daisy, such as describing her "gray haze of fur collar" and her outfit as "white" before her encounter with Tom and Gatsby.

San Diego County is exceptionally fertile due to its mild and sunny climate. Common crops include tomatoes, citrus fruits, leafy greens, squash, broccoli, herbs, tree fruits such as peaches and lemons, berries, honey, and peppers. There is a strong demand for organic community supported agriculture (CSA) in the San Diego region, with many local organizations boasting long waiting lists for their services. Organic eggs and milk are also popular purchases. Many organic farms offer tours of their operations and access to recreational activities like hiking and birdwatching. This setup allows landowners to benefit from government programs while enhancing habitat, promoting recreational use, and creating opportunities for farm tours and educational programs.

Organic farming typically offers greater biodiversity in plants and wildlife due to the absence of chemicals. However, it can be more labor-intensive and costly than conventional farming, as it requires intensive management to control pests and weeds and maintain soil fertility without chemicals. Additionally, organic farms may experience higher losses and lack the economies of scale enjoyed by larger operations. Certain practices beneficial to wildlife, like planting cover crops, strategic grazing rotation, and invasive species removal, also require more labor. Therefore, landowners in this scenario might seek financial assistance or expertise to balance profit and habitat quality.

The land in question is a 160-acre parcel near Potrero, in unincorporated San Diego County, bordering the Cleveland National Forest. This land includes chaparral, nonnative Mediterranean grassland, and oak woodland, and is part of the East County Southern Foothills ecoregion in the San Diego Multiple Species Conservation Plan. The plan currently recognizes over a hundred species of plants and animals, with many being endangered, such as the Stephens' kangaroo rat, mountain yellow-legged frog, several butterfly species, and the California gnatcatcher, and others are declining and may soon be listed as endangered, like burrowing owls.

This land has a rich history of habitation by Native Americans for centuries and was later settled by cattle ranchers and cordwood sellers in the late 1800s. It was part of an original homestead and likely used for grazing and wood production for many years. After researching available government programs, a model organic farm in the same area was identified as a potential example of what could be achieved with this land.

Culture is a crucial factor in any negotiation. It can be understood as much by its absence as by its presence and significance. Culture is not uniform or isolated. Blanket statements like "all Russians are stubborn" or "all Japanese are accommodating" are too simplistic. While it's helpful to grasp the general traits of a culture, a skilled negotiator should focus on how the culture's attitudes affect the negotiation process. When encountering a foreign culture, it's natural to relate it to one's own culture, leading to inevitable comparisons. Understanding a foreign culture or mindset may involve delving into its history, understanding its biases, and accepting it for what it is, rather than trying to change it. This is especially important if you're in a weaker bargaining position or in "away" territory. Cultural nuances extend beyond national borders, as individual companies often have their own distinct cultures, influencing factors like work hours, communication styles, and hiring practices. Some companies may encourage or restrict employee philanthropy. Even cultures that appear uniform can have deep layers. Understanding a culture's values, which provide its "why," is equally important. For instance, if a culture values saving face or communal harmony, a negotiator will refrain from public humiliation. Similarly, a negotiator from a culture that values aggressive bargaining will not relent easily. Before negotiation, it's beneficial to learn about one's opponent's personal background to enhance the process.

The statement "There is no God" was supposedly made by a fool, as written in Psalm 14 of the Christian Bible, and is the starting point for St. Anselm's argument about God's existence. This belief is shared by another author we'll discuss, Thomas Aquinas. Since both are defending the same idea, and we're to compare their arguments, we'll assume they both believe in the Bible's God for simplicity's sake. Assuming any other god wouldn't allow a fair comparison, as their arguments are specific to this concept. However, both arguments fall short of providing a comprehensive basis for believing in God. To illustrate this, let's first look at St. Anselm's main argument. He proposes that we find truth about God within our own understanding. He argues that because we can't imagine God's non-existence, we can thereby prove his existence. This idea, though complex, suggests that the proof for God lies within our own minds, not requiring external evidence. This is often referred to as faith in Christian texts. In contrast, St. Thomas Aquinas advocates for proving God's existence through reason and empirical evidence alone, without needing faith. His five logical arguments, including change, causation, contingency, degrees of excellence, and harmony, suggest that God's existence can be deduced from logic.

Around the 5th or 6th century BCE, a future Buddha was born. He left the worldly life, achieved enlightenment, and his teachings eventually led to the formation of Buddhism, with Theravada Buddhism being the most traditional branch. This religion is now about 2500 years old and has evolved significantly since Buddha's time, evident in practices like the annual water-cutting ceremony in Sri Lanka, where monks and laypeople participate despite Buddha not teaching such rituals. These changes span from superficial traditions to the religion's core beliefs. Theravada Buddhism, both from the monastic and lay perspectives, has had to adapt its doctrines over time due to both external and internal influences, both friendly and hostile.

Throughout this discussion, several terms will be used. Internal forces are those originating from within the Buddhist community, while external forces come from non-Buddhists. Hostile forces harm or intend to harm Buddhism, while benign forces do not wish to harm the community but may inadvertently do so. These terms will be frequently used.

First, let's explore the core of Theravada Buddhism. Buddhists find refuge in the Three Jewels: the Buddha, the Dhamma, and the Sangha. The Dhamma includes the Tripitaka, three collections of texts: the Sutta Pitaka (containing Suttas), the Vinaya Pitaka (disciplinary rules), and the Abhidhamma Pitaka (metaphysical concepts like Anatta, Dukkha, and Anicca). Understanding these concepts helps one break the cycle of Sansara (death and rebirth), along with its components: lobha (desire), dosa (hatred), and moha (delusion). When one becomes enlightened, these cease. The Vinaya Pitaka outlines rules for laypeople (five precepts) and monks (many more). Fundamental to Buddhism is the Four Noble Truths: life is suffering (Dukkha), attachment causes suffering, suffering can be overcome, and there is a way to achieve this.

America and Mexico once had a long-standing rivalry that lasted from 1836 to 1893, with the Mexican-American War of 1846-1848 serving as the peak of their conflict. Other disputes also occurred between the two nations, with the rivalry subsiding just before World War I. The animosity began due to disagreements over religion, culture, and economic interests, not unlike many border-sharing nations. David M. Pletcher (1977) notes that only Mexico and Cuba posed long-term challenges to U.S. diplomacy due to their proximity and rivalry. Religious tensions, rooted in historic distrust between the English and Spanish, were a significant obstacle to friendly relations. Diehl and Goerts (2000) enumerate 17 disputes, mainly involving territorial issues caused by raids and outlaw activities across the border. Schmitt (1974) attributes the easing of the rivalry to Mexico's growing dependence on the U.S. and the shift in American aims from territorial expansion to economic intervention in Mexico in the late 19th century.

Fifteen years ago, I was unexpectedly struck by a previously unknown illness that left me disabled. At the time, I was a nurse, having chosen this career to ensure safety and security, driven by my childhood experiences and the reassuring mantra that "You'll always be able to find work; people will always get sick." Even though my dream was to become a scientist or journalist, I chose nursing. Yet, here I am, at 46 years old, single, and unable to work. After 15 years on Social Security Disability, I have nothing to call my own, and daily struggles assault my sense of security, safety, and self-esteem. Nothing in my life is certain anymore, but I know that without the support of my family and some good friends, I wouldn't have lasted this long. When disaster truly strikes, you feel incredibly weak, no matter how strong you are.

My point is that life throws emergencies at us, big and small, and no matter how well we prepare, some challenges are too great to face alone. While I agree that Americans should not rely solely on big government, I believe we should instead focus on rebuilding trust and mutual support. The Conservatives in the U.S. praise "rugged individualism" as the foundation of our country, but our forefathers' resilience came from compassion, mutual respect, and shared resources. Pioneers didn't cross the Rockies alone in wagon trains.

Therefore, while I advocate for preparation, I also urge you to connect with your neighbors and form a support network. I have a disaster kit with first aid supplies, water purifying tablets, and other essentials. If you have the ability and resources, consider starting a small farm and preserving your own food, or even having a wood stove, but always remember that building a strong community is equally important.

Why do organisms change over time? What factors influence the direction of their evolution? While in 1917 D'Arcy Thompson remarked that "Even now the zoologist has scarce begun to dream of defining in mathematical language even the simplest organic forms," this sentiment still holds true today. Recently, mathematical modeling has been used to study general aspects of mollusk skeletogenesis across both ontogeny and phylogeny (e.g., Raup and Stanley, 1981). Our research aims to explore how mathematical modeling of ontogenetic and phylogenetic changes in Prunum, combined with experimental studies, can help understand the mechanisms behind the direction and magnitude of evolutionary-developmental changes. We used X-radiographic images of Prunum species to identify quantitative parameters, which were then used to model hypothetical and actual skeletal morphologies with the software program CerioShell (Stone, 1995). These models, along with experimental and descriptive studies, help us better grasp macroevolutionary events in this group.

A shell can be visualized as a structure that moves through 360 degrees of space over time. These loops or turns of a coiled shell are called whorls, which spiral around an imaginary central axis called the columella. The rate at which whorls enlarge can vary, and a continuous line separates each whorl, known as a suture. In most shells, the largest whorl is the last, called the body whorl. The spire consists of all whorls except the last, with the apex being the tip and the base the opposite end. The aperture is the opening through which the animal extends out of its shell.

Shells can be viewed from apical, basal, apertural, and abapertural perspectives. The "usual" orientation is an apertural view, with the aperture facing the viewer and the apex pointing up.

A method for counting whorls involves first viewing the shell from the apical perspective and determining where the first suture begins. A line can then be drawn to divide the shell into two parts, from which whorls are counted and estimated to a quarter of a whorl.

A shell can be seen as a series of apertures that traverse through time and space as the animal grows its shell. The path of the aperture can be traced using the coordinates of the centers of each whorl's aperture, as well as the horizontal and vertical radii of the aperture. This trajectory can be graphically and mathematically represented. Once a mathematical formulation is established, parameters can be varied and modified to alter the mollusk’s skeletogenesis.

Indonesia's neonatal and infant mortality rates have remained relatively unchanged over the past decade. While the nation is progressing towards several Millennium Development Goals, such as water and sanitation targets, the progress in child and maternal health lags behind what's needed to meet the 2015 goals. This disparity is due to several factors, suggesting that it's crucial to bolster the overall healthcare system rather than focusing solely on specific programs.

Indonesia has seen an increase in births attended by skilled healthcare workers, with 72% now meeting this criterion. However, these skilled workers often include traditional midwives who are unable to handle medical interventions, leading to higher maternal mortality due to complications like hemorrhage. This improvement is somewhat misleading, as there's still significant work to be done. Additionally, the percentage of children under five receiving professional treatment for diarrhea has decreased, and there are concerns about postnatal care, as data is incomplete but shows low rates nationwide.

Cesarean section rates remain low at 4%, with a notable disparity between urban (7%) and rural (2%) settings. This highlights an issue of healthcare access, with most services concentrated in urban areas. Further, there's a significant gap in service utilization between the poorest and wealthiest quintiles (27%), indicating that the poor face greater barriers in accessing healthcare services, likely due to out-of-pocket costs.

When considering strategies to enhance neonatal and maternal care indicators, the primary question is which approach is most effective in addressing the lack of services. Should Indonesia prioritize program-specific interventions or strengthen the overall healthcare system without targeting pre- and postnatal care for mothers and children? While programmatic approaches offer targeted, manageable goals and faster results, they also have drawbacks. Heavy investment in specific areas can lead to funding shortages and human resource imbalances, potentially causing program duplication and increased paperwork for supplies and funding.

Victorian novels are distinguished by their meticulous attention to detail and focus on the aristocracy of the era. Two exceptions are Oliver Twist and Wuthering Heights, which incorporate elements of mystery and the unusual, unlike other novels of the time, which enhances the characters' development. These novels often employ dream sequences or dreamlike states to convey mystery, which serves different purposes in each case.

In Oliver Twist, these dreamlike sequences provide insights into Oliver's inner turmoil, revealing his emotional and psychological state, as well as his awareness of the true nature of events around him. For instance, when he relives the shooting in Chapter 28, it feels like a dream, highlighting Oliver’s lack of control over his fate and the desperate state of his health. The passage emphasizes his inability to regain control of the situation, as he doesn’t notice the unseen force that takes him away, and he experiences constant, fear-driven pain. This event suggests that Oliver has little agency over his life and that his despair is growing, potentially due to the influence of Fagin. It implies that if Oliver had any capacity to react, he would have tried to save himself, but he is overwhelmed and defeated.

The day passed – the day seemed to pass – and night fell again; night that was long and silent, yet brief, like a fleeting dream.

A few years ago, I worked in an after-school tutoring program for elementary students. While I assisted them in various subjects, my proficiency was greatest in English and reading. A colleague asked me to help a boy named Adrian, who was having significant difficulty with reading. I soon realized that Adrian understood some letters perfectly but struggled with others, which seemed unusual. Adrian was of Latino descent and spoke fluent English, which made his situation puzzling. We faced challenges until I met Adrian's mother. During a field trip, she arrived to pick him up, and I realized she spoke only Spanish. With my limited Spanish, we managed to communicate, and I discovered that Adrian could read but was unfamiliar with the English alphabet. I don't know if this insight helped him much, but I hope he's doing better now.

This story highlights the complex issue of language barriers in schools, particularly in California. Even a child who speaks perfect English might struggle with reading due to unfamiliarity with the English alphabet. This problem is evident, and while solutions exist, they are not straightforward. For children like Adrian, who spoke fluent English but needed help with the alphabet, tutoring was effective. For those who speak little to no English, the challenge is more complex.

The dual language system could be beneficial. While it's often feared to be resource-intensive and ineffective for most students, research shows that children in these programs outperform their peers. However, implementing it as a standard practice rather than an exception would benefit all students. Special bilingual aides or tutors can help, but requiring all teachers to be bilingual isn't practical. Combining different approaches, such as dual language programs, mainstream immersion, private tutors, and ESL classes, is key to addressing this issue.

From a young age, many of us are taught about something beyond our comprehension, often through religious instruction or personal introspection. While some embrace the faith of their parents, others reject it, preferring their own perspective. Regardless of our chosen path, we strive to define our spirituality through our unique views. We seek guidance in the darkness to lead us into the light.

“A cardinal,” my father replied when I asked about his favorite type of bird. We sat on our porch, listening to the rain as we shared cigarettes. The gutters overflowed, drenching the plants along the edge. He gazed into the rain, his eyes reflecting a mix of searching and reminiscing. He appeared thinner, his hair less dense than before. I was overwhelmed by his condition and struggled to discuss how much I'd miss him. Instead, I hugged him and sat closer, joining him in watching the rain.

My father passed away in December, five days after my twenty-second birthday. The treatments prolonged his suffering, but I couldn't watch him die. I chose to remember him by his life, not his death. I stayed in bed for three days, waiting for news. No one contacted me.

The "Gothic Novel" is, in essence and name, an "old-new" oxymoron, as Ian Watt describes in The Rise of the Gothic Novel. The Gothic mode has been both criticized and praised, accused of lacking depth and celebrated for its 'terrible sublime' quality (Burke). The original "Gothic Novel," Horace Walpole's The Castle of Otranto, combined the ideas of ancient and modern romances to create the proto-Gothic genre and a new mode of literary expression. Walpole employed old theatrical elements and modern mimicking of nature in contemporary novels to present what he called "A Gothic Story" (Walpole 4). The Gothic genre continues to draw upon medieval gothic theatre, architecture, and traditions, despite the term "gothic" originally being used to describe various peoples, styles, and time periods. Initially seen as archaic or unsophisticated against "modern" societal and literary advancements, the blend of the more theatrical "Gothic" and the novel format that allowed readers a deeper look into characters' psychology has enabled Gothic literature to endure and remain both obsolete and fresh to readers from different time periods.

One key idea present in Gothic novels is the concept of Chivalry. The medieval idea of chivalry, training a proper knight, is both preserved and transformed in the original Gothic novel, The Castle of Otranto. Chivalry is significant to Gothic writers because it embodies the ideal of a brave, honorable, and competent knight, and the perceived or supposed lack of such qualities in contemporary society. By employing chivalric concepts and manners, the "gothic past" is idealized and romanticized, hinting at Gothic's evolution towards Romanticism, and used to strive for improvement in the present. Writing during a politically turbulent time and possibly despondent over the future, Walpole may have felt that the morality and inherent goodness present in the gothic era had been lost in contemporary society. This perspective is evident in several characters, such as Frederic, who embodies many chivalric traits. Before meeting Frederic, he is described as a:

The description of him includes traditional chivalric elements: Frederic is a prince, has suffered tragedies, and is presumed to have been killed by infidels. The figure of the "gallant and courteous Knight" is exaggerated, introducing the soon-to-be typical Gothic trope of excess (66).

Supply chain management involves the series of steps that take an order from a customer back through the stages of raw materials, production, and distribution, delivering the product to the customer. The term was coined by Keith Oliver in 1982 as a way to describe the planning, execution, and control of the supply chain to meet customer needs efficiently. Six key components make up a supply chain: production, supply, inventory, location, transportation, and information. Business managers use these components to enhance customer service. Production, the first step, forms the basis for the entire supply chain. It involves deciding what, when, where, and how to produce goods based on customer demand, which is typically determined by market analysis. Managers must consider market conditions and customer preferences to decide on the products to produce and their quantities. They also need to choose the optimal location for production, balancing volume, quality, and cost. After setting the production location, managers focus on scheduling and equipment maintenance. This step is crucial as every detail impacts the overall process. For instance, retail giants like Wal-Mart and Target have detailed processes and procedures for every aspect of their operations, reducing confusion and ensuring smooth workflow. Supply, the second key element, involves making strategic decisions about facility capabilities and outsourcing partnerships. Companies may have multiple divisions for a single product, each with unique equipment, workers, and expertise. Managers must select the best division for each product process. Outsourcing can help achieve velocity, the ability to provide quality and flexibility while controlling costs.

Hitler exists in Burma, according to the sign.

Ellen Page, star of Juno, stands alone at a street corner with a cardboard sign above her head, bearing a disturbing message written in Sharpie. Burma, also known as Myanmar, is a Southeast Asian nation controlled by an oppressive military regime that took power through a coup d'état in 1962. In 2007, public protests led by Buddhist monks, dubbed the "Saffron Revolution," occurred following a decade of silence. Initially, the Burmese government tolerated the monks' peaceful demonstrations, but it soon escalated into a violent conflict with the military. Foreign journalists were detained and a Japanese photojournalist, Kenji Nagai, was killed on September 27th, 2007, for covering the protests. The official death toll stands at 13, but Colonel Hla Win, who defected from the army, claimed thousands had been killed.

This is not a new phenomenon. Throughout history, governments have sought to suppress dissent and maintain absolute control over their citizens. Early Roman emperors claimed divine right to rule, Japanese emperors were believed to be gods, and U.S. President George W. Bush supposedly had weekly meetings with Ted Haggard, leader of Stupid People Worldwide, a Conservative Party affiliate.

Famous examples include the 1989 Tiananmen Square protests, where intellectuals, labor activists, and students protested the government's authoritarian rule, with official reports ranging from 200-3,000 dead. The Rwandan genocide in the 1990s saw Hutu militia groups, backed by the Rwandan government, systematically kill Tutsis and political moderates. Hitler's Third Reich, a period spanning several years and countries, resulted in widespread persecution and murder of Jews.

Duke Ellington's enduring influence in jazz is largely due to his longevity and his ability to guide his orchestra. Although his piano playing is often subtle, Ellington excelled as a composer, crafting intricate pieces that highlighted the unique talents of his band members. He created a framework that allowed soloists to improvise freely, while also writing pieces that showcased the specific styles of his players. This approach not only emphasized the tone of the orchestra as a whole but also resulted in some of the most innovative and brilliant jazz compositions of all time.

The Grove Music Dictionary highlights Ellington's sound and innovation by referencing "Creole Love Call." This piece, which uses the voice as a jazz instrument, demonstrates Ellington’s early use of vocal texture and color without lyrics. The piece, a slow twelve-bar blues with six choruses, showcases several soloists, including a muted trumpet, clarinet, and his voice itself. In "Hot and Bothered," recorded the following year, Ellington's orchestration and ear for tone color are evident in a call and response between a muted trumpet and scat singing. The song "It Don't Mean a Thing (If It Ain't Got That Swing)" further exemplifies this, with Joe "Tricky Sam" Nanton using his muted trombone to introduce the melody.

She had always felt a void, a longing that remained unfulfilled. This feeling began when she was 14, entering her teenage years, and persisted at 17, even though she had decided she wanted someone rather than an object. Despite boys being drawn to her, none sparkled her interest. She often wondered why this was, but her thoughts didn't yield satisfying theories. So, she lived her life, always curious about her desires.

At home, life was usually serene. Her parents were peaceful and harmonious, rarely arguing even with their daughter, except when she asserted her independence. She was their lively, lovable daughter, a stark contrast to their calm nature.

Today, however, was far from serene. As she moved from room to room in search of inspiration, she heard her mother's scream from the kitchen. Running in, she found her mother on the floor, in pain. Quickly, she asked for assistance and rushed her mother to the car. The hospital's antiseptic scent filled the air, but her mind was focused solely on helping her mother.

Her mother had lost her balance while climbing a step stool to reach a high cabinet.

This research aimed to demonstrate that sticking closely to a "Mediterranean Diet" (Med diet), measured by a high "alternate Mediterranean (aMed) diet score", correlates with a reduced likelihood of developing chronic heart disease (CHD) and stroke, as well as stroke-related deaths. The aMed diet is a variant of the Med diet that emphasizes higher consumption of plant-based foods (excluding potatoes but including fruits, nuts, whole grains, and legumes), monounsaturated fats (over saturated fats), and fish, while limiting intake of animal products and saturated fats. Moderate alcohol consumption is permitted.

Previous observational studies have shown an inverse relationship between adherence to the Med diet and the risk of total and cardiovascular (CVD) mortality. An intervention trial also found that the Med diet was more effective than a low-fat diet in promoting weight loss and reducing the ratio of total to high-density lipoprotein cholesterol in overweight individuals. Prior studies did not specifically focus on stroke or stroke mortality.

This study tracked 74,886 women aged 38 to 63 years, who were part of the Nurses' Health Study, a cohort study of 121,700 female nurses in 11 US states. Over six periods from 1984 to 2004, researchers calculated an aMed diet score using self-reported "food frequency questionnaires" (FFQs) to assess nutrient intake over the preceding year. Over 95% of nurses maintained their involvement throughout the 20-year period. FFQs underwent validation studies. Reports of CHD, fatal CHD, and stroke were confirmed by medical or hospital records, autopsy, or death certificates. Where documentation was unavailable, cases were classified as "probable" and included, with about 17% of all strokes and 24% of nonfatal myocardial infarcts so classified. Body mass index, smoking status, aspirin use, multivitamin intake, menopausal status, and postmenopausal hormone use were calculated for each FFQ, and beginning in 1986, leisure-time physical activity was assessed.

To minimize random variation and better capture long-term dietary intake, cumulative averages of the aMed score from the repeated FFQs were calculated (by averaging scores from two prior years). Adjustments were made for potential confounding factors (variables that could skew results) by adjusting for age, smoking, BMI, menopausal status, postmenopausal hormone use, multivitamin intake, alcohol intake, physical activity, and aspirin use.

Cox proportional-hazard modeling was used to examine the association between an aMed score and the risk of CHD and stroke, using separate models for fatal and nonfatal CHD and stroke types.

Greater adherence to the Mediterranean diet, as indicated by a higher aMed diet score, was linked to a lower risk of incident CHD and stroke in women. Over 20 years of follow-up, 2391 incident cases of CHD, 1763 incident cases of stroke, and 1077 cardiovascular disease deaths (fatal CHD and strokes combined) were identified. Women in the top aMed quintile had a lower risk for both CHD and stroke compared to those in the bottom quintile (relative risk [RR], 0.71).

In 2007, the United States faced a severe financial crisis, characterized by rising unemployment, a collapsed housing market, and the demise of many prominent financial institutions. This economic downturn continues today, prompting the question: what caused this crisis, and how can we prevent future occurrences? The crisis was largely a result of shortsighted and self-interested political decisions that compelled banks and corporations to issue sub-prime loans within an inadequately developed financial system. Meanwhile, Fannie Mae (FNMA) and Freddie Mac (FHLMC) were pressured to back and repack these mortgages into mortgage-backed securities (MBS) and credit default swaps (CDS). When borrowers defaulted on these loans, banks lacked sufficient capital reserves, which led them to transfer the resulting turmoil onto the repackaged mortgages and into the broader economy.

The seeds of the financial crisis were planted during the Clinton administration in 1999, as the president sought a second term. To boost his popularity, he loosened lending restrictions, setting the stage for the sub-prime mortgage crisis seven years later. Steven Holmes of the New York Times warned at the time, "Fannie Mae, the nation's leading home mortgage underwriter, faced pressure from the Clinton Administration to expand mortgage lending to low and moderate-income individuals, and faced pressure from shareholders to maintain its remarkable profit growth." Holmes accurately predicted the consequences, stating, "The government-subsidized corporation may face trouble in an economic downturn, requiring a government bailout similar to that of the savings and loan industry in the 1980s." As the introduction mentions, and Holmes foresaw, ill-advised lending led to the economic collapse.

Several factors contributed to the economic downturn, including the complex structures of mortgages. The widespread use of adjustable-rate mortgages, mortgage-backed securities, and collateralized debt obligations (CDOs) in the years leading up to the crisis further interwove different sectors of the economy with the housing market. This increased leverage made U.S. households and financial markets highly sensitive to even minor price fluctuations. When the housing bubble burst, financial institutions that had purchased these mortgage-backed securities suffered significant losses. The top five U.S. investment banks collectively held $4.1 trillion in mortgage debt in 2007, accounting for around 30% of the USA’s GDP. Ultimately, Bear Stearns and Merrill Lynch were sold at bargain prices, Lehman Brothers was dissolved, and Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley were forced to become heavily regulated commercial banks. Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac, with $5 trillion in mortgage debt, were placed under government control in September 2008.

Exposition: The section of your narrative where you spread your wings and captivate your audience with your enthralling prose, or where you risk losing your readers' attention. Dr. Merlin has had her share of frustration while dealing with this part, often finding herself amidst a flurry of unnecessary details. Despite the well-known advice to "show, not tell," many writers, including Dr. Merlin, still struggle with exposition, often giving too much background information too quickly.

Exposition is the part where you simply inform the audience about past events, often in straightforward language. In movies, it's when one character shares a long monologue of information, like "The Rime of the Ancient Mariner." In fiction, this is done by the author.

Consider this example: While reading a story, you're told that the main character met her love, got married, and then lost him. You wouldn't expect this entire backstory to take up two pages with limited dialogue. Instead, you'd expect the author to flesh out the husband's character, showing his love for his wife through his words and actions. The same goes for the heroine, where her character should be evident through her interactions with him. This way, you'd feel the emotional impact of his death and connect with the heroine's experience more deeply.

In essence, you need to add substance to the bare facts of the story. Sometimes, the urge to rush through certain details is strong. Perhaps you're introducing a new character who was once in the Air Force, now runs a gas station, has been married twice, likes fishing, dreams of owning the gas station, and had Eggs Benedict for breakfast. Instead of just stating these facts, incorporate them into the character's actions and dialogue.

I tuned in to two news broadcasts from Columbus, Ohio. The first live broadcast was from NBC 4 this morning (August 13, 2011). The lead story reported a man named Shad Hostettler who stabbed his wife in Ashley, Ohio. They aired his mug shot, and he appeared to have a menacing appearance. The story was given minimal coverage, dedicating only about two minutes to it. The details were scant, mentioning only that he had stabbed her multiple times and was arrested. I think the time spent was appropriate.

The second story was about a young man named Travis Buyers, 18, who had been critically injured in a shooting in the Sharon Woods area. There were no arrests or suspects at the time, and the SWAT team was investigating. This story seemed rushed, and I believe this could be due to it involving a minority individual. I've often noticed that crimes against minorities are less frequently reported or receive less attention. On the other hand, crimes against whites, especially children, are often heavily covered by the media.

The next story discussed a bullet hole found in a Med-Flight helicopter. Details were given on the incident's location, and it was determined to be a .22 caliber rifle bullet. Crime-Stoppers offered a $5,000 reward for information leading to the shooter's arrest.

The following story warned about rain and thunderstorms predicted for Saturday afternoon. They mentioned temperatures would be in the mid to low eighties for the weekend. The report was brief but served as a teaser to keep viewers tuned in.

Another story covered a robbery at a Clime Road UDF in Columbus. The suspect was described as a dark-skinned black man, about six feet tall and weighing 150 pounds, dressed in a hoodie sweatshirt. The story seemed to emphasize his race and skin color more than necessary.

The final story discussed Rene Rodriguez, a convicted Texas drug kingpin sentenced for distributing marijuana in large quantities from Texas to Ohio. Instead of saying 25 years, they mentioned 300 months. It's unclear why they used this phrasing, possibly to make it sound more severe. They also mentioned he was Hispanic, which seemed irrelevant to the story.

The bond between brothers is profound and unshakable, encompassing a range of emotions such as love, pride, jealousy, and even cruelty. Brothers possess a deep understanding of each other, often seeing themselves reflected in their siblings. This intimate bond is most evident in dire situations, where both positive and negative emotions can be exposed. Understanding the complexities of this fraternal bond involves acknowledging the consequences that come with it. By looking into a brother's eyes, one sees not how they are perceived by others, but their true self. Their character is revealed through their actions and the consequences of those actions. In “The Scarlet Ibis”, two brothers delve into this theme, facing the turmoil of their emotions in a vividly described landscape. A climax of bitterness and intense pride leads to one brother's demise. The story explores this theme through the protagonist's, Doodle's, direct characterization and their interactions, as well as the narrator's perspective, which conveys the protagonist's feelings and his worldview, significantly influencing his actions. The protagonist's motivations can be distilled to a single emotion: pride. Starting from their first outing together to their final, fateful trip, he harbors resentment towards Doodle. He longed for a brother who could learn and participate in various activities like holding his breath, running, or climbing trees, but Doodle's heart condition made this impossible. The protagonist initially feels anger towards Doodle, even considering harming him at one point, yet a simple smile from Doodle melts his heart, revealing his underlying love and weaker resolve.

The human brain is an intricate, innovative information-processing system. As technology evolved from primitive to advanced, so did the metaphors used to represent the brain. Initially, it was likened to a wax tablet, then a sheet of papyrus, followed by a book, and most recently, a computer. As you delve into understanding the brain, keep in mind the limited usefulness of these metaphors and their potential to lead to incorrect conclusions.

Information processing begins with sensory organs converting physical stimuli such as touch, heat, sound waves, or light into electrochemical signals. This sensory information is repeatedly transformed through the brain's algorithms in both bottom-up and top-down processes. For instance, when looking at a picture of a black box on a white background, bottom-up processing compiles simple data like color, orientation, and border changes to identify the box. Top-down processing utilizes decisions from these bottom-up processes to accelerate recognition of the box. In this example, top-down processing might help you classify the object as a black box rather than a hole.

Once information is processed, an attention filter determines its importance and which cognitive processes it should be made available to. For example, while your brain processes every blade of grass when you look down at your shoes, a healthy attention filter prevents you from noticing them individually. Conversely, you might pick out your name even in a noisy room. The processing of information involves multiple stages, with results repeatedly modulated by attention.

To process information, the brain must first store it. There are various types of memory, including sensory, working, and long-term. Information is initially encoded based on its type of sensory input. For example, verbal input can be encoded structurally (how the word looks), phonemically (how it sounds), or semantically (what it means). Once stored, information must be maintained. Animal studies suggest that working memory, which holds information for about 20 seconds, is maintained by an electrical signal looping through specific neurons for a short duration. Long-term memory is hypothesized to be maintained in the structure of certain proteins.

There are numerous theories on how knowledge is organized in the brain, some based on human memory retrieval, others on computer science, and others on neurophysiology. The semantic network model posits that knowledge is organized into nodes representing concepts, with nodes linked based on their relatedness. For example, in a semantic network, "chair" might be linked to "table," which can be linked to "wooden," and so on.

Aldous Huxley critiques the impending threat of technology and capitalism through his dystopian novel, Brave New World. The societal structure prioritizes community over individuality and promotes immediate happiness, conditioning citizens from birth. People are pawns in a larger system dictated by the World Controller. Examining the novel through Marxist lenses reveals Huxley's concerns about these developments. The novel employs Marxist terms like homogenization and reification to highlight issues with the emerging capitalistic economy. Capitalism is satirized through the concept of false consciousness, where the common people are kept unaware of their true economic relations and focused solely on personal gain. This is achieved through ideological control, evident in the conditioning of people in Brave New World. Lower classes, such as Deltas and Gammas, have no autonomy, with hypnopædia reinforcing their desires to consume. Hegemony, where a group dominates another, is also present in the World State. The lower classes are unaware of this manipulation, 'buying into' the ideology that supports capitalism. Upper classes, like Alphas and Betas, are aware but accept their position. The novel's lack of meaningful relationships between characters and the superficiality of interactions reflect the loss of free will and expression. Love and strong emotions are absent, as are meaningful interactions; men discuss women's physical appearance, and women discuss their encounters. Each class's acceptance of their status in the hierarchy illustrates the socioeconomic impact of capitalism, with people believing they are superior due to their consumption and obedience.

I've been a student at University Park for roughly 2.5 years, which equates to about 4.5 semesters. Navigating the campus can be challenging for many students, including myself. During my freshman year, I was assigned a dorm room in East Halls, the farthest eastward point on campus (excluding the stadium and Bryce Jordan Center). Walking from Stuart Hall to classes in locations like the Willard building, situated near the campus center, could take up to 25 minutes, especially in bad weather, which is common in State College. An alumnus, not much older than me, shared that in the past, the East Halls dorms were secluded by large tracts of empty land. Today, that space is occupied by sports fields, new buildings such as the new Creamery and health services building, and apartments, as the campus continues to expand, making it increasingly difficult to move from one place to another. The most effective solution for this mobility issue is cycling, but simply having bikes isn't enough. Students need to use them, and the campus must be designed to accommodate cyclists. My friend who recently resumed cycling after a few years mentioned that he couldn't understand why he ever stopped. “Bikes are great,” he said, “they’re the only viable way to get around.” Cycling is not only efficient but also beneficial for one's health. A bowl of oatmeal and a bit of physical exertion can cover 30 miles or more. Like many students, I now reside off campus, just as far from the center as some dorms. The best decision I made this year was to buy a bike. My daily class in Thomas building, which is a 25-minute walk from my home, can be reduced to 5 minutes by cycling. The main problem is that Pollock Road, the most direct route to Thomas building from my house, isn't always easy to navigate on a bike. Although walking also has its merits, I don't have the time. Without a bike, walking would be my only dependable option for getting to class. Daily walks to Thomas would consume an extra 30-40 minutes, totaling around 2.5 hours a week. Adding the time spent walking to and from other classes, appointments, and so forth, that's more time than I can afford to spare.

original_texts:
In pursuing an education in social work, I intend to follow a career path with the Division of Family and Children Services to help children who have been abused or neglected; and to provide support for troubled families. Values that I can provide to the social work field include the following: service, respect, ethical nature, commitment to help improve relationships between others and to improve myself professionally to remain competent in my field. These core values are not just important to social workers; they are important to me personally. 

	I have always wanted to help others, but I was unsure of the career path that I wanted to follow. Throughout my years in high school and college, I saw many individuals flee from their problems in denial and a few used coping mechanisms that were less than ideal. Because of situations that I have witnessed, I chose to pursue a Bachelor’s degree in Psychology. Still unsure of a career path, I decided to take a break once I graduated from Piedmont College in 2009. One day that summer, I visited a friend who introduced me to a sixteen year-old boy sitting nervously on her couch. She explained to me why he was visiting: to escape his abusive parents. The next day, I learned that he had called the police to his parent’s residence. To see if I could help in any way, I drove over to his parents’ house. Once there, I privately explained my concerns to the police and told them I had just graduated with a degree in Psychology from Piedmont College. The police requested that I talk to the parents since there was nothing that the law could do for the teenager. When I questioned the parents about the situation, they seemed nervous and used excuses to describe their son’s “manipulative” behavior for involving outside sources to resolve “simple” disputes. After this particular experience, I began to seriously consider a career in social work to help children with “simple” disputes among family members.

	Another value that is important for the field of social work is social justice. As a society, we claim that the individual is important and we mourn those that we have lost. The concept of the “individual” that society holds is more a follower of archaic traditions than actual uniqueness. So, if society mourns lost individuals, then why do we strive to be similar to “everyone else?” I am an individual and do not enjoy placing limitations on myself to be similar to others. Throughout my years at high school and college, I protested against social injustice whenever I could: coloring my hair unnatural colors, wearing clothing that fit my personality, piercing my ears past the traditional set, declaring my involvement with GSBA (Gay Straight Bisexual Alliance), fighting against both racism and discrimination whenever I witnessed it, etc. I believe in social justice and I will continue to protest against social injustice.

The following paper addresses the Biological and Sociocultural models in relation to the disorder insomnia. The biological model focuses on genetic information that is inherited as well as medical aspects of health. The Sociocultural models look at environmental relationships and their applications to race, ethnicity, demographics, and socioeconomic status. The following review of insomnia looks at these models and explains each piece of research chosen to relate to and to better explain the models. The explanations of the research and their findings are then critiqued to mention their specific strengths and weaknesses.

A sleep disorder can be characterized as a primary sleep disorder, a sleep disorder related to another mental disorder, or a sleep disorder related to other issues. The Primary sleep disorders are Dyssonmias or Parasomnias while sleep disorders related to another mental disorder are related to an Axis I or Axis II disorder. Other categories of sleep disorders can be due to medical complications or the intake of a substance. The Dyssomnias are: Primary Insomnia, Primary Hypersomnia, Narcolepsy, Breathing- Related Sleep Disorder, Circadian Rhythm Sleep Disorder, and Dyssomnia Not Otherwise Specified (NOS). While Primary Insomnia is a complication in adequate or maintained sleep, Primary Hypersomnia is a difficulty in staying awake, both for at least a one month period of time. Narcolepsy involves cataplexy and/ or automatic REM. While Dyssonmias focus on initiating and remaining asleep, the Parasomnias are sleep disorders associated with behavioral abnormalities and/ or physiological occurrences. Parasomnias are Nightmare Disorder, Sleep Terror Disorder, Sleepwalking Disorder, and Parasomnias Not Otherwise Specified. The sleep disorders related to another mental disorder involve sleep difficulties due to Axis I (Clinical Disorders) or Axis II (Personality Disorders or Mental Retardation). The following review focuses on insomnia, and somewhat on primary sleep disorders in general in relation to the biological and sociocultural models.

	 The biological model of sleep disorders focuses on genes, heritable factors, and physiologically acquired aspect of sleep disorders. Neurons in the hypothalamus containing orexin are responsible for the regulation of sleep and wakefulness. This study experimented with mice and found that there are phenotypic GABAB receptors on the orexin neurons which are specifically responsible for sleep/ wake states. The activation of the GABAA receptor induces responses that promote sleep. If it is inhibited from firing, this can cause reduced anxiety and induce sleep. The GABAB agonist (baclofen) increased sleep time (Matsuki et al., 2009). Such results imply that the animal models of mice can be generalized to studies in humans. This shows that there is a genetic and environmental basis for the physical GABAB receptor in humans. A problem or absence with this receptor could alter the ability of one to have adequate sleep without medication. The sociocultural implication of this study is that if the phenotype was inherited, this could regulate sleep, and an alteration of the receptor would naturally disturb sleep for an individual. This would negatively impact aspects of life such as school, career, and every day events that involve monotonous tasks and focus.

This paper covers three areas of Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD). First, a brief definition of the disorder is provided. Next, diagnosis is explained, with common characteristics, or “red flags”. Finally, the paper concludes with ways that a teacher in a mainstreamed classroom environment can assist a student with CAPD.

	Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD), or Auditory Processing Disorder (APD) “refers to the efficiency and effectiveness by which the central nervous system (CNS) utilizes auditory information. Narrowly defined, (C)AP refers to the perceptual processing of auditory information in the CNS and the neurobiologic activity that underlies that processing and gives rise to electrophysiologic auditory potentials” (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005), meaning it is a disorder wherein the central nervous system (i.e. the brain) cannot properly process things that are heard. People with CAPD can hear normally, and are therefore not considered “hearing impaired”; rather, the area of the brain that translates what we hear, separating words or differentiating conversation from background noise does not function as it typically should. 

	The earliest mention of the disorder that became CAPD is from the mid-1950s, called “auditory imperception” (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005) when researchers were evaluating children with communicative disorders. The Italian research team of Bocca, Calearo, and Cassinari began developing tests for these children in 1954; in 1961, Kimura “introduced dichotic testing and formulated a model to explain the physiology of the CANS underlying dichotic perception” (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005). A national conference was held in 1977 that stimulated research on children with CAPD. 

	CAPD manifests itself in multiple ways: the person suffering may not be able to localize or hear sound in space; may have difficulty discriminating between two or more “acoustic events” (sound occurrences); may not be able to recognize sound patterns; may not be able to differentiate changes in speech (like detecting sarcasm based on change of voice); one sound may be blocked by a subsequent sound; may not have the ability to synthesize sound clues (that is, interpret in a meaningful way that they can then act upon); and may not be able to determine the sequence in which auditory information is presented (Ferre).

	In order to diagnose CAPD, the patient must be screened with “systematic observation of listening behavior and/or performance on tests of auditory function”, which may be conducted by “audiologists, SLPs, psychologists, and others using a variety of measures that evaluate auditory-related skills” (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005). This may include questionnaires and surveys, observation of auditory behaviors, including how the patient responds to certain stimuli. There is, at this time, no one tool or test that is used consistently to a high rate of diagnostic success, and there is no known cause for the disorder. Many tests used present the patient with multiple, simultaneous auditory stimuli and then ask for them to differentiate certain items, like a series of words or numbers. More advanced tests include recording acoustic signals within the ear and measuring the responses to the signals.

The play Twelfth Night seems to say that although disguise is in fact useful in perpetrating long bouts of deception, in the end a person must reject that newly formed guise, or else risk losing themselves forever in the process. A big problem with ending a deception, however, is that one may find themselves alienated in the process. Therefore, in the end, one must decide between one’s own self preservation, or the preservation of relationships with those around them. For although some will respond neutrally to discovering that they’ve been tricked, still others will not take the deception so lightly, and will be likely be offended by the whole charade.
The topic of deception in gender role reversal is especially problematic, because it brings up many side issues, perhaps the most important one being, why? Why does the subject feel the need to shirk their own identity and take up a disguise in the form of the opposite gender? In Viola’s case, it is obviously a form of self protection.: “I’ll bring you to a captain in this town/ Where lie my maiden weeds, by whose gentle help/ I was preserved to serve this noble count…” (5.1.247-249)
Having newly arrived in a foreign land, Viola feels it necessary to pretend to be a man to protect herself from would be attackers. Viola’s plan works, but it also alienates her from the women around her, cutting her off from an important support system. To make matters worse, she is apparently so convincing at appearing to be a man that Olivia confuses her with Sebastian, and in effect falls in love with her. “Whither, my lord? Cesario, husband, stay.” (5.1.138) On top of that, she also has to deal with suppressed romantic desires between her and Orsino: “Boy, thou hast said to me a thousand times/ Thou never shouldst love woman like to me.” (5.1. 260-261)
Although this may be a somewhat progressive attitude, to the modern reader, Twelfth Night may be seen as an illustration of how deception may help facilitate the unveiling of suppressed emotions, especially in the cases of Olivia and Orsino. Certain passages seem to hint that the aforesaid characters may have unexpressed subconscious desires that the appearance of Viola/Cesario forces them to deal with. For instance, is Olivia attracted to Cesario because Cesario appears to be a man, or does Olivia really secretly harbor feelings for women? One would argue that this is probably not the case, because Shakespeare’s character Olivia seems more likely to be parodying those people of his time period who judge others only upon their looks. 
This is evidenced by the ease with which Olivia switches her romantic ardors from Cesario to Sebastian, and begins to regard Cesario/Viola as family rather than a love interest: “A sister, you are she.” (5.1.315)

German colonial rule has been noted by various observers for its brutality, notably with respect to the genocide of the Ovaherero and Nama in German South West Africa. Of course nothing so broad as an entire colonial empire can be accounted for by such a simple description. The German colonial empire was as varied in policies and ruling style as it was in geography. Educational provision across the colonies was similarly diverse. When the British took over German East Africa (Tanganyika) in 1919, they found a large population of educated and literate Africans. German educational efforts in Kamerun and other colonies were also praised by contemporary authors. 
The situation in South West Africa (present-day Namibia) presented a stark contrast.  Unlike in East Africa, where the government established state schools and played a prominent role in the education of the natives, in South West Africa the task of native education was left almost entirely to missionary societies that received limited government support. The government did however invest significant resources towards the education of Europeans in the colony, establishing s system of state schools as well as more heavily supporting and regulating missionary schools. These educational policies had longstanding effects on South West Africa, even after German rule. While other German colonies boasted significant numbers of literate and educated Africans, in South West Africa “the overwhelming majority of the population remained untouched, uneducated, and illiterate.” Various social, political, and economic factors led to the divergent experience of South West Africa. This paper seeks to expand the discussion by identifying these factors and paying particular attention to new research on the attitudes of settlers and colonial authorities to native Africans.
There is a wealth of literature dealing with education in the German colonial empire specifically. Most of these sources are in German and were written in the early twentieth century, during or shortly after the period of German colonial rule. The aim of early works was primarily to describe the features of educational systems in these colonies. Later writings in English expanded the discourse through comparative studies of education in the various German colonies and more detailed analyses of specific aspects of education. These studies illustrated significant differences in the educational systems of different colonies. The most prominent work to explicitly address the topic of this paper is Cohen’s study of education in South West Africa and East Africa. Cohen compares the educational systems of the two colonies and discusses the factors that account for the differences between them. According to Cohen, the large settler population of South West Africa explains many of the distinguishing aspects of the colony’s educational system.
Compared to Germany’s other colonial possessions, South West Africa had a moderately temperate climate, although much of the territory is covered by arid desert. The European population of South West Africa reflected the relatively hospitable conditions. By 1913 nearly 15,000 whites lived in South West Africa, while only 5,336 lived in the colony with the next largest settler population, East Africa.

‎	‏The classification of Popular Music has grown over the past‭ ‬100‭ ‬years to include so many genres that it is difficult to definitively list them all. Complicating matters,‭ ‬most if not all genres—rap,‭ ‬rock,‭ ‬country,‭ ‬jazz,‭ ‬folk,‭ ‬just to name a few—have spawned multiple sub and sub-sub genres within their domain.  Arguably the sub-genre of Heavy Metal rock has become one of the most diverse and expressive genres of all popular music in the past‭ ‬40‭ ‬years. It is expressive because it displays a wide range of emotions,‭ ‬although they tend to lean toward the darker side of the spectrum. It is diverse in that quite soon after the beginnings of the genre,‭ ‬people started to realize that it had real flexibility and started to take advantage of it to create their own sub-genre,‭ ‬which then was followed by sub-sub-genres,‭ ‬and the chain continues until today. 

Today we have reached a point in the heavy metal movement where there are so many niches of groups that it is hard to determine what exactly heavy metal is. It has grown to incorporate so many themes from other genres,‭ ‬but like everything else,‭ ‬it spawned from somewhere. In order to properly understand the metal music that exists everywhere today,‭ ‬one must first understand what the metal movement is,‭ ‬and why it’s a movement rather than just a genre.

‎	‏Metal is,‭ ‬in many ways,‭ ‬a movement defined by darkness. Metal can be considered a‭ “‬music of more‭”—‬more bass,‭ ‬more volume,‭ ‬more violence,‭ ‬more theatricality. Less primitivism,‭ ‬more chops‭; ‬people in metal bands really know how to play their instrument,‭ ‬and it comes through in the music. Metal is also—although it may not come as a surprise—a movement that is heavily drug induced. There was a psychedelic drug boom in the mid-70‭’‬s that led to people getting crazier,‭ ‬leading to them to make crazy,‭ ‬other-worldly records,‭ ‬using the drugs as a scapegoat for their creation. It possesses many dark,‭ ‬visceral qualities,‭ ‬which was very new to the music scene because a large amount of popular music had qualities that weren’t true to the darker side of the emotional spectrum. Also,‭ ‬later generations of metal have taken some of their influence from the dark,‭ ‬visceral qualities that were so present in the Romantic Era. Lyrics such as the following express the darkness that is such a staple of the movement:‭ (‬Byrne‭)‬


	
These lyrics from Helter Skelter display the darker side of the Beatles. It exhibits an up and down,‭ ‬supposedly that of drugs. This song is considered by some to be one of the first Heavy Metal songs. It was a response to a Rolling Stones song that was also on the heavier,‭ ‬darker side. The Beatles wanted to prove that they could be just as heavy as the Stones,‭ ‬so they put that song on‭ ‬The White Album.

A few decades before the Surrealist artists began painting their dreamlike works, the artist Henri Rousseau was carefully crafting his own dreams, literally and figuratively. The Dream, a 1910 painting by the famous Post-Impressionist artist, represents not only a woman in awe at the wonders of the land she visits within a dream, but also Rousseau’s own personal dreams and goals as a painter. Since beginning his work, he dreamed of recognition, acceptance, and praise by other artists and art lovers, and found that he was faced with a difficult internal dilemma to achieve this aspiration. The Dream is Henri Rousseau’s work that best reflects his career-long internal struggle: to either conform to or mimic certain styles of painting in order to be accepted by the critical art world he so adored, or to allow himself to be creatively independent and unique, leaving his own path as he went.
Before one can analyze The Dream through this perspective, one must first be somewhat familiar with Rousseau’s biographical story. Henri Rousseau was born on May 21, 1844, in the town of Laval in northwest France. His father was a tinsmith and hardware dealer who “enjoyed bourgeois prosperity” (Shattuck 47). Growing up, he received no formal training in the arts; instead, he was employed until the age of forty working for France as a gabelou, or employee of the municipal toll service, although he received the misnomer sobriquet of douanier, a customs inspector (Shattuck 46). The death of his first wife, Clémence, which followed the deaths of eight infant children, left Rousseau with only one child, a daughter named Julia, and immense grief (Shattuck 49). He therefore hoped to take refuge in a new life and pursued painting to offer him comfort and fresh beginnings. Unlike contemporary colleagues of Rousseau who sentimentalize and romanticize the peasant in painting, he is essentially a folk painter and has the hopes and dreams of the average member of his class.
Rousseau’s obsession with being accepted by the art world is somewhat understandable when evaluated in context: as discussed, he was not only uneducated in the ways of formal painting and began his career at a much older age, but he was producing works at the same time as many other talented and better-known modern artists. Though working for many years already, Rousseau did not begin to receive proper recognition for his art until around the same time that Matisse had begun crafting a reputation as an artist. In the book Modern French Painters, author Jan Gordon asserts that the two, while technically competitors in the art arena, were different not only in style and subject matter but also their reasons for painting in the first place: “Matisse was a painter who conceived a terror of painting in a trite way, while Rousseau’s desire was to paint a picture so conventional that he would be admitted to the Artiste Français” (92).

Many a great thinker has postulated an intimate connection between ethics and aesthetics, between truth and beauty. I believe that at a fundamental level there is a reason for this.
