Foreign journalists were rounded up and imprisoned on sight, with a Japanese photojournalist named Kenji Nagai killed on September 27th, 2007, simply for being present at a street protest. While the official death toll rests at 13 killed, Colonel Hla Win, who defected from the army some days prior to the official report, is quoted as having said, “Many more people have been killed in recent days than you’ve heard about. The bodies can be counted in several thousand.”

This is nothing new. While these are some of the most recent examples of atrocities taking place in our world, a government’s desire to quash dissent and maintain complete rule over its citizenry has been around for as long as civilization itself. Early Roman emperors declared themselves chosen by the gods to have complete executive ruling over every aspect of their society. Japanese emperors are believed to actually be gods, sent to our world to lead their people to prosperity through the invention of Motorola cell phones and hara-kiri, and our current president, George W. Bush, has weekly conference calls with Ted Haggard, the leader of Stupid People Worldwide, a subsidiary group of the Republic Party.

Some of the most well known examples of these actions are such incidents as the 1989 June 4th protest at Tiananmen Square, where intellectuals, labor activists, and students all gathered to protest the authoritarian rule of the government. The death toll in that particular instance ranges wildly, with official reports from the Chinese government stating 200-300 dead to reports let out by the Chinese Red Cross, declaring between 2,000-3,000 dead.  Another is the Rwandan genocide of the 1990s, where Hutu militia groups, aided by the Rwandan government, began a systematic killing of all Tutsis, as well as political moderates, irrespective of their ethnic backgrounds. Hitler’s ‘Third Reich’, a period spanning several years and several countries where anyone of Jewish background was rounded up and killed, is another extreme example.

Duke Ellington’s legacy in jazz derives in large part from his longevity and, by extension, his creative abilities to shape his orchestra. Ellington’s presence on the piano is subtle in many of the compositions selected for this assignment, but as a composer Ellington excelled at creating rich and complex pieces that showcased the individual abilities of band members. Ellington crafted the framework in which a soloist could freely improvise, in addition to writing tightly orchestrated pieces and phrases that called on the particular style of band members to highlight musical ideas. In doing this, he also emphasized the tone of the orchestra more generally, creating coherent and original sounds to fit each piece. Ellington’s mastery of the individual players’ sound, as well as how they fit together in a growing ensemble, enabled him to write some of the most innovative and brilliant pieces in jazz history.
The Grove Music dictionary, in discussing Ellington’s sound and innovation, mentions Creole Love Call in reference to using voice “as a jazz instrument” throughout his career.  This is an early example of Ellington’s use of voice to add texture and color without the hindrance of lyrics. Creole Love Call also demonstrates Ellington’s ability to compliment the style of his soloists, something that is evident throughout his career. This slow, deliberate twelve bar blues piece contains six choruses, as follows:
Chorus 1: Call and response between voice and reeds, where the voice begins smooth and melodic, then transitions to a rougher sound towards the end.
Chorus 2: Muted trumpet solo that elaborates on the basic melody and emphasizes several extended blue notes.
Chorus 3: Sweeping clarinet solo in a high register, backed by a subtle syncopated piano phrase.
Chorus 4: Full band echoes the first chorus with a call and response by the brass and reed sections.
Chorus 5: The climactic chorus of the piece, as the reeds now begin the call and response in a high register, backed by syncopated stop time from the brass and rhythm sections.
Chorus 6: A return to the structure of the first chorus, with call and response between voice and reeds. In this chorus the voice takes on the sound of the “growl” technique, soloing as an instrument.
Tag: Brief tag featuring a vocal run and a dissonant novelty ending by a trombone.
Ellington’s use of voice to add a dimension of tone color to this piece is one example of a stylistic trait that permeates his work. 
In Hot and Bothered, recorded a year later, Ellington combines his skill at tight orchestration with his ear for tone color. A call and response phrase between “Bubber” Miley on muted trumpet and Baby Cox’s scat singing uses the vocal elements of Miley’s playing and instrumental aspects of Cox’s voice to create a rich and complementary sound. It Don’t Mean a Thing (If It Ain’t Got That Swing) extends these ideas, as Ellington uses Joe “Tricky Sam” Nanton, a mainstay in Ellington’s orchestra, to great effect in introducing the melody on muted trombone.

She had always felt like she needed something. It was this desire that refused to be fulfilled. It started when she was about 14, just getting into a teenage life. And it was still there 3 years later, at the age of 17. By now, she had determined she wanted someone rather than thing. Yet, she had felt no interest in any boys. Some had been attracted to her, gone through the awkward attempts to woo the un-woo-able, but no one appealed to her. She questioned herself often with this strange notion, trying to think of what it was that could possibly cause such a strange thing to happen with a teenage girl. The few years of contemplation had brought up theories, but nothing good enough for her to really speculate on. So she lived life, continually questioning her desires.

A day at home was usually a peaceful thing. Her parents were good and calm people. They never argued with each other and oddly enough, arguments with their daughter were very seldom. The only thing they ever argued about was her asserting her independence and free personality. She was the daughter of a very calm couple, but she definitely countered their energies with her extensive and fun personality which made her very like-able in combination with the fact she was a nice person.

Today, though, was not a calm day. As she walked from room to room, attempting to find some new inspiration for her own her, she heard a short scream from the kitchen, the sound of her mother's beautiful voice. She ran into the room, starting to panic as she frantically questioned, "Mom?! Mom, what's wrong?!" She saw her mother lying on the ground, appearing to be in pain as she continually kept saying "Ow" in short breaths. The mother's daughter ran to her side and put a hand on her to attempt assistance. "Ouch ... swee - ty, I ... need you to take me to - the hospital." The words were rushed and squeezed and her daughter could tell she was in immense pain. "Okay Mom, just tell me where I can pick you up." Her mother directed her hands and at this moment, the hero of the house was very grateful she had taken classes to strengthen herself. She carried her mother to the car, set her in the back lying down, and drove.

A visit to the hospital brought scents of disinfectant and sickness, laced with fear. But she wasn't sensing that, as her mind was too occupied with helping her mother. She carried the injured woman in quickly and started calling for help from the doctors. A few worried faces gathered around and someone quickly pulled up a rolling bed and laid her mother down on it. They took her to be immediately looked at, and her daughter was left to sit in worry.

Her mother had fallen off of a stepping stool while attempting to grab a vase from the highest cabinet they had.

This study was to show that adherence to a “Mediterranean Diet” (Med diet), as reflected by a high “alternate Mediterranean (aMed) diet score”, is associated with reduced risk of chronic heart disease (CHD) and stroke and stroke mortality.  The aMed diet is a modified version of the Med diet and is characterized by higher consumption of plant foods, including plant proteins (excluding potatoes, but including fruits, nuts, whole grains and legumes), monounsaturated fat (compared to saturated fat) and fish, and lower consumption of animal products and saturated fats.  Moderate intake of alcohol is allowed.
  	

Prior prospective studies documented an inverse association between adherence to a Med diet and risk of total and cardiovascular (CVD) mortality and an intervention trial showed the Med diet to be more effective than a low-fat diet, in promoting weight loss and lowering the ratio of total to high-density lipoprotein cholesterol in obese individuals.  Prior studies did not focus on stroke or stroke mortality.


This epidemiological study followed 74,886 women, 38 to 63 years of age, without a history of CVD or diabetes, who are participants in the Nurses' Health Study, a cohort study of 121,700 female nurses in 11 US states.  Six times, from 1984 to 2004, the authors computed an aMed diet score from self-reported “food frequency questionnaires” (“FFQs) designed to assess nutrient intake during the preceding year.  More than 95% of nurses continued participation throughout the 20 year period. FFQs were subjected to validation studies.  Reports of CHD, fatal CHD and stroke were confirmed by review of medical or hospital records, autopsy or death certificates. Where records were not available, cases were considered “probable” and included, with about 17% of all strokes and 24% of nonfatal myocardial infarcts so classified. Body mass index, smoking status, aspirin use, multivitamin intake, menopausal status and use of postmenopausal hormone were calculated for each FFQ, and beginning in 1986, leisure-time physical activity was assessed. 

To reduce random variation for an individual and better represent long-term dietary intake, cumulative averages of the aMed score from the repeated FFQs were calculated (averaging together scores from two prior years).  Adjustments were made for “confounders” (factors that could confuse results) by adjusting for age, smoking, BMI, menopausal status, postmenopausal hormone use, multivitamin intake, alcohol intake, physical activity and aspirin use.

Cox proportional-hazard modeling was used to assess the association between an aMed score and risk of CHD and stroke, using separate models for fatal and nonfatal CHD and stroke types. 

Greater adherence to the Mediterranean diet, as reflected by a higher aMed diet score, was associated with a lower risk of incident CHD and stroke in women.  During 20 years of follow-up, 2391 incident cases of CHD, 1763 incident cases of stroke and 1077 cardiovascular disease deaths (fatal CHD and strokes combined) were found. Women in the top aMed quintile were at lower risk for both CHD and stroke compared with those in the bottom quintile (relative risk [RR], 0.71).

In 2007, the United States of America fell into a crushing financial crisis. Unemployment increased, the housing market crashed, and many of America’s largest and most important corportations were left in ruin. This recession persists today, so we must ask the question: how did this crisis occur, and how can we stop it? In short, the financial crisis was created by selfish and naïve political decision-making that pressured banks and firms into issuing sub-prime loans into an already immature and unsufficient financial infrastructure. Meanwhile, Fannie Mae (FNMA) and Freddie Mac (FHLMC) were pressured to underwite and repackage these mortgages into CDO’s and CDS’. When borrowers defaulted on these loans, the banks were short on capital reserve and transferred this chaos onto the repacked mortgages that they had sold, and on to the rest of the economy.
	The financial crisis had its roots in 1999 of the Clinton era, as the President was aiming for a second term in office. He sought to extend his presidential tenure by augmenting his popularity. To accomplish this the Clinton administration relaxed lending restrictions, which helped to set the grim stage for the sub-prime crisis seven years later.  Steven Holmes of the New York Times reported in 1999, “Fannie Mae, the nation's biggest underwriter of home mortgages, has been under increasing pressure from the Clinton Administration to expand mortgage loans among low and moderate income people and felt pressure from stock holders to maintain its phenomenal growth in profits.” Holmes would go on to correctly foresee the consequences of these actions: “But the government-subsidized corporation may run into trouble in an economic downturn, prompting a government rescue similar to that of the savings and loan industry in the 1980s.” As detailed in the introduction, and as Holmes foresaw, ill-advised lending would certainly lead to the meltdown of the economy.
	Many factors combined to throw the economy into tailspin, one of which was the new and complex structure of mortgages. Adjustable-rate mortgages, mortgage-backed securities, and collateralized debt obligations (CDO’s) were all used extensively in the years leading up to the crisis, and only served to intertwine more sectors of the economy into the housing market. This led to U.S. households, and financial markets in general, to overleverage themselves in the housing market, leaving them extremely vulnerable to even small changes in price. 
	Indeed, the housing bubble burst, and the financial institutions that had bought these mortgage-backed securities were spited. The top five U.S. investment banks all together reported $4.1 trillion dollars of mortgage debts in 2007, which accounted for about 30% of the USA’s GDP. In the end, Bear Sterns and Merrill Lynch were sold exceptionally cheap, Lehman Brothers was dismantled, and Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley were forced to become commercial banks subjected to intense regulation. Fannie and Freddie were $5 trillion in mortgage debt, and were placed under government control in September 2008.

Ah, exposition.  That place in your story where you stretch your little writer's wings and take flight, astounding one and all with your magnetic, nay magical prose.  Or the part where your readers fall asleep and/or hit the "Back" button while cursing your name.  Dr. Merlin has been known to shout at her monitor when she finds herself in the middle of Too Much Information, and not even in the fun way.

Exposition is not your friend.

My gentle readers already know the basic writing tip, "Show, don't tell," but Dr. Merlin still stumbles into long passages of text where nothing happens, or worse, too much.  Exposition is the little devil sitting on your shoulder that says to get the history out of the way to get to the good parts (not to be confused with the devil sitting on the other shoulder urging the author to tell her audience every single detail of the childhoods of each character).

Exposition means telling the audience what happened, typically in simple prose.  In film, the exposition happens when one character tells another a core-dump of information ala "The Rime of the Ancient Mariner."  In fiction, the author's doing the telling.

An example is in order.  As you are reading a story, you are told that the heroine met her beloved at such a place and time, that they were married in a gala fashion, and that her husband was murdered in front of her eyes.  You would not expect this entire sequence to take two pages, during which time both he and she only get two lines of dialogue each.  You would expect the author to spend some time on the husband's character, evidencing by his speech and manner how deeply he loves his wife, and you would equally expect the heroine to show through big and small ways how much his presence in her life changed and enriched her (especially if the story were to tell you flat out later that this was the case).  A proper introduction to the husband's character would allow you to become emotionally involved with his fate and would give you insight into the heroine's character: what she saw in him, how deep their bond was, clues about her thoughts and beliefs and dreams as reflected through the prism of his eyes, and so on.  You would mourn his death with her, and so grow more connected to the heroine herself.

In short, you would expect meat on the simple bone of the storyline: "They met, they married, he died."

As a writer, you need to provide that meat.  (*looks at metaphor, sighs, plunges onward*)  Sometimes it is tempting to rush past certain things.  Perhaps you're introducing a new character and you know he used to be in the Air Force, and he's the night manager of a gas station now, and he was married twice, no kids, likes to go fishing on the weekends, secretly dreams of owning the gas station someday and had Eggs Benedict for breakfast.

I watched two newscast’s from Columbus, Ohio. The first one that was “live” was NBC 4 this morning (August 13, 2011). The lead story was about a man in Ashley, Ohio who had stabbed his wife, it did not state her name however his name was Shad Hostettler. They showed his mug shot and he looked like pure evil. They devoted only about two minutes to this story as it was developing. The only details they provide he had stabbed her multiple times and had been arrested. I think they spent an appropriate amount of time on this story. 
	The second story was about an early morning shooting of Travis Buyers, 18. He was shot in the Sharon Woods area and had been critically injured; there had been no arrests made at the time or any suspects. The SWAT Team was investigating the crime. This story seemed to be short, and I believe that might have been due to the fact this was a “black” man or a black neighborhood. I noticed (and have for years) that minorities are glossed over when they are a victim of a crime. If say a “white” child or adult is kidnapped or missing or a victim of a crime the media goes nuts; but if a minority person it’s lucky if it is even mentioned. 
	The next story was about the gunshot hole that had been found in the Med-Flight helicopter. Details were given about where they thought the incident happened. It had been determined that it was a .22 caliber bullet from a rifle that had hit the helicopter. Crime-Stoppers are offering a five-thousand dollar reward for tips that lead to the arrest of the shooter. 
	The next story was concerning the rain and thunderstorms predicted for Saturday afternoon. They said the temperatures would remain in the mid to low eighties for the weekend. The length of time was a little short, but they wanted to use it as a “teaser” so that you would stay tuned. 
	They also ran with a story about a robbery of a Clime Road UDF in Columbus. They said it was dark-skinned black man who robbed the store he was wearing a hoodie sweatshirt. They said he was about six-foot tall and weighed about one hundred and fifty pounds. I thought they devoted an unusual about of time emphasizing he was black and how dark he was. 
	Another story was about a Rene Rodriguez who was a convicted Texas Drug-Kingpin. He had been convicted of conspiring to distribute marijuana in large amounts to Ohio from Texas. One curious thing I noted, was instead of saying he was sentenced to twenty-five years in prison they said “300” months. I am not sure what the angle was there, whether they thought that sounded more harsh or what. They also mentioned he was a Hispanic man, I don’t believe that was really germane to the story.

There is a bond between brothers; an unbreakable, irrevocable bond. Within that bond lie many emotions: love, pride, jealousy, and cruelty, just to name a few. Brothers understand one another, far more than anyone else with that kind of bond, and they can only see themselves when looking at their brother. It is when a situation is at its most dire when the true nature of this bond shines through, be it good or evil. When these emotions become clear, they carry with them great a cost. Part of understanding the emotions born of this fraternal link is dealing with the consequences that they bring. When one can look a brother in the eye and see within that person their own reflection, they see themselves not as others see them, but as they truly are. In their actions and the consequences of those actions is where their true character lies.  In “The Scarlet Ibis”, two brothers explore this theme, and all of the raging emotions that accompany it. Throughout a lush, vividly described landscape, these two boys set out on a futile journey. Bitter disappointment clashes with intense pride in the climactic scene, and only one brother escapes with his life. The theme is expressed through direct characterization of the protagonist, Doodle, and their interactions with each other, as well as through the narrator’s point of view, which communicates the complex feelings experienced by the protagonist and his view of the world around him, both of which are heavy influences on his actions.
	The protagonist’s actions can all be summed up by one key emotion: pride. From the time he and his little brother, Doodle, first go out together, to their final, fateful excursion, the protagonist feels resentment towards Doodle. He had wanted a brother whom he could teach all of his worldly skills, like “…holding my breath, running, jumping, or climbing the vines in Old Woman Swamp…” He wanted a brother who could fill the role of “…someone to race to Horsehead Landing…and someone to perch with in the top fork of the great pine behind the barn…” Obviously these things are impossible, given Doodle’s condition. Doodle was born with an extremely weak heart, making in unlikely he would even survive. Even then, it was nearly impossible that he would ever participate in vigorous physical activity. What a blow to the young protagonist, his head filled with wild fantasies, to have all of those dreams crushed in an instant. In fact, he is even shown to bear some anger towards the small child, as he recalls beginning to contemplate killing him by suffocating him with a pillow. What kind of child would have the presence of mind to consider infanticide? However, his heart melts when the small child smiles at him. Such a simple act gave the protagonist such hope! This shows that his conviction probably was not very strong. In the back of his mind, he had an instinctive love for his brother.

The human brain is a complicated, creative information-processing system. As technology advanced from primitive to modern, the metaphors used to describe the brain also advanced. Initially, it was compared to a wax tablet, then to a sheet of papyrus, then to a book, and most recently, to a computer. As you learn about the brain, keep in mind that the usefulness of these metaphors is limited and can lead to erroneous conclusions.
Information processing starts with input from the sensory organs, which transform physical stimuli such as touch, heat, sound waves, or photons of light into electrochemical signals. The sensory information is repeatedly transformed by the algorithms of the brain in both bottom-up and top-down processing. For example, when looking at a picture of a black box on a white background, bottom-up processing puts together very simple information such as color, orientation, and where the borders of the object are – where the color changes significantly over a short space – to decide that you are seeing a box. Top-down processing uses the decisions made at some steps of the bottom-up process to speed up your recognition of the box. Top-down processing in this example might help you identify the object as a black box rather than a box-shaped hole in the white background.
Once information is processed to a degree, an attention filter decides how important the signal is and which cognitive processes it should be made available to. For example, although your brain processes every blade of grass when you look down at your shoes, a healthy attention filter prevents you from noticing them individually. In contrast, you might pick out your name, even when spoken in a noisy room. There are many stages of processing, and the results of processing are modulated by attention repeatedly.
In order for the brain to process information, it must first be stored. There are multiple types of memory, including sensory, working, and long-term. First, information is encoded. There are types of encoding specific to each type of sensory stimuli. For example, verbal input can be encoded structurally, referring to what the printed word looks like, phonemically, referring to what the word sounds like, or semantically, referring to what the word means. Once information is stored, it must be maintained. Some animal studies suggest that working memory, which stores information for roughly 20 seconds, is maintained by an electrical signal looping through a particular series of neurons for a short period of time. Information in long-term memory is hypothesized to be maintained in the structure of certain types of proteins.
There are numerous models of how the knowledge is organized in the brain, some based on the way human subjects retrieve memories, others based on computer science, and others based on neurophysiology. The semantic network model states that there are nodes representing concepts, and that the nodes are linked based on their relatedness. For example, in a semantic network, “chair” might be linked to “table,” which can be linked to “wooden,” and so forth.

Aldous Huxley criticizes the upcoming threat of both technology and the capitalistic structure by which it is reinforced through the creation of a dystopia in the novel Brave New World. Its people value community above the individual, and are conditioned from the very beginning to pursue immediate happiness above all else. The citizens are revealed to be pawns in a larger game, confined to one ideology as dictated by the World Controller. By examining the work under the lenses of Marxist theism, one notices the underlying suspicions of the author in regards to the development of aforementioned systems. Frequent terminology in Marxism, such as homogeny and reification, among others, reinforce the idea that Huxley’s novel is a commentary on the faults in the emerging economy from his time on.
Capitalism is satirized through the use of the Marxist thesis known as false consciousness. Essentially, the common citizenry is prevented from knowing true relations to other classes in economic terms, as they are primarily interested in their own gain. It is said to be the result of ideological control of the proletariat and common laborers, something quite obvious by the conditioning of the people in Brave New World. The common classes, Delta, Gamma, etc., have no true will of their own; through hypnopædia the drive to consume, to spend, to indulge is strengthened above all else.  This is manipulated, as previously stated, by the World Controller.  Hegemony, essentially the idea that groups of social classes are dominated by  a separate group of individuals in totality, is obviously used in this case. The lower classes are entirely unaware of the manipulation, quite literally ‘[buying]  into an ideology that supports that structure’ (i.e. capitalism & consumerism). ’ Upper classes are born with the ability to be aware of it but do nothing ; few Alphas or Betas beyond characters like Bernard do much more than likewise accept their place.  In fact, the  interactions of the social classes, as will be discussed  in greater length, are significant indications of the perceived oppression of capitalism.
Relationships between disparate individuals does not exist in Brave New World.  The novel seemingly refuses to distinguish the characters - they are, even  among major characters, lacking depth. Perhaps Huxley is suggesting that the rise of technology and capitalism together deprive man of their free will and expression. Love does not exist, nor do the extremes of any one emotion; rather, interactions are kept superficial, portrayed distinctly through  the males remarks  about women primarily about their physical appearance (i.e. pneumatic quality), and the females’  unashamed  comments about their encounters, so to speak.  Furthermore, each societal class’ complacency with their status in the hierarchy  indicate  the socioeconomic effect of capitalism.  Their absolute obedience of their part in the community is an indication of Marxist thought on the proletariat, who are falsely ensured of their own superiority over all else so long as they continue to consume, to obey, to stay in line with the rest of their peers.

I have been a student here at University Park for about two and a half years now, or four and a half semesters. For many, including myself, getting around on campus can be a problem. My freshman year I was placed in an East Halls dorm room; pretty much the furthest eastward limit of campus, not counting the stadium and Bryce Jordan Center. Traveling from my home in Stuart Hall to classes in such faraway places as Willard building, near the center of campus, could take up to 25 minutes by foot, especially if the weather was bad, as it often is in State College. Speaking to an alum not much older than myself, I learned that not long ago the East Halls dorms were set apart from the rest of the school by huge tracts of unused land. Today that empty space has been filled with sports fields, huge new buildings including the new Creamery and new health services building, and surrounded with apartments. As our campus continues to expand, getting from one place to another becomes more and more difficult. What is the best solution to the problem of mobility? On a college campus, it is the bicycle. But the bike by itself won't solve any problems. Students need to ride them, and the campus needs to be built to suit the needs of bicyclists.
	I was talking to a friend of mine who recently resumed bicycling after a several-year hiatus. He mentioned that he wondered why he ever stopped. “Bikes are great,” he said, “for a few years it wasn’t cool to ride a bike, but it’s the only way to get around.” In addition to being good for your body, bicycling is the most efficient way to travel. A bowl of oatmeal and a little physical exertion will take you 30 miles or more. Like many undergraduates, I now live off campus; just as far from the center of campus as some dorms. The smartest decision I’ve made this year was to buy a bike. Every day, I have class in Thomas building, easily a twenty-five-minute walk from my home. Riding a bike can cut that time down to 5 minutes if I pedal fast enough. The only problem is, Pollock Road is the straightest shot to Thomas building from my house, and it's not always an easy road to travel on, bike or no bike. There are things to be said for walking as well, but personally I’m too busy to walk. If I didn’t have my bike, walking would be my only reliable option for getting to class. Walking to Thomas every day would take an extra 30-40 minutes out of my day. That’s over two and a half hours every week. Add to that all the other time I would have to spend walking to and from other classes, appointments, and etc. That’s more time than I can spare.

In my pursuit of a degree in social work, I aim to work with the Division of Family and Children Services to support children who have faced abuse or neglect, and to assist troubled families. I can contribute the following values to the field: dedication to service, respect for others, integrity, a commitment to fostering healthier relationships, and a drive to continually improve my professional skills. These values are not only essential for social workers but are also deeply personal to me.

Growing up, I have always desired to help others, although I was unsure of the specific career path. Throughout high school and college, I witnessed many people avoid confronting their problems through denial or unhealthy coping mechanisms. These experiences led me to pursue a Bachelor’s degree in Psychology. After graduating from Piedmont College in 2009, I took a year off to consider my career path. One summer, a friend introduced me to a 16-year-old boy who was escaping from his abusive parents. He had called the police to his home. I offered to help and visited the parents, discussing my concerns with them. The parents appeared nervous and blamed their son for involving outsiders in trivial disputes. This experience sparked my interest in social work to help resolve family conflicts.

Moreover, social justice is another crucial value in social work. Society claims to value individuality but often promotes conformity. I believe in the uniqueness of each person and advocate for social justice by protesting against injustices, such as wearing unconventional clothing, supporting LGBTQ+ rights, and standing against racism and discrimination. I will continue to champion social justice throughout my life.

This document examines the Biological and Sociocultural models in relation to insomnia. The Biological model centers on inherited genetic factors and medical aspects of health. Sociocultural models, on the other hand, explore environmental influences related to race, ethnicity, demographics, and socioeconomic status. The ensuing review evaluates insomnia and other primary sleep disorders through these models, explaining each selected study and critiquing its strengths and weaknesses.

Sleep disorders can be classified as primary, secondary to another mental disorder, or resulting from other health issues. Primary sleep disorders include Dyssomnias and Parasomnias, while those linked to mental disorders are associated with Axis I or Axis II disorders. Other sleep disorders may be due to medical complications or substance use. Dyssomnias encompass Primary Insomnia, Primary Hypersomnia, Narcolepsy, Breathing-Related Sleep Disorder, Circadian Rhythm Sleep Disorder, and unspecified Dyssomnias. Primary Insomnia is characterized by difficulties in initiating or maintaining sleep, while Primary Hypersomnia involves challenges in staying awake. Narcolepsy involves symptoms like cataplexy or automatic REM sleep. Parasomnias are characterized by behavioral abnormalities or physiological events during sleep, including Nightmare Disorder, Sleep Terror Disorder, Sleepwalking Disorder, and unspecified Parasomnias. Sleep disorders related to mental disorders involve sleep difficulties associated with clinical (Axis I) or personality (Axis II) disorders.

The Biological model of sleep disorders emphasizes genes, inherited traits, and physiological aspects. Neurons in the hypothalamus containing orexin regulate sleep and wakefulness. A study using mice discovered that GABAB receptors on orexin neurons are responsible for sleep-wake states. Activation of GABAA receptors promotes sleep, while inhibition can reduce anxiety and induce sleep. Baclofen, a GABAB agonist, increased sleep duration in the study. This suggests that findings from animal models can be generalized to humans, indicating a genetic and environmental basis for GABAB receptors. Impairments in these receptors could hinder adequate sleep without medication. Socioculturally, if the genetic trait is inherited, it could influence sleep, and alterations in the receptor could disrupt sleep, negatively impacting daily life activities.

This paper examines three aspects of Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD), also known as Auditory Processing Disorder (APD). Firstly, it provides a concise definition of the disorder. Secondly, it outlines the diagnostic process, including common signs, or "red flags". Finally, it offers suggestions for how teachers in inclusive classrooms can support students with CAPD.

Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD) or Auditory Processing Disorder (APD) refers to the efficiency and effectiveness of the central nervous system (CNS) in utilizing auditory information. Specifically, (C)AP involves the perceptual processing of auditory information in the CNS and the underlying neurobiological activity that generates electrophysiological auditory potentials. In essence, it is a condition where the brain cannot properly process what is heard. Individuals with CAPD can hear normally but struggle with separating words or distinguishing conversations from background noise.

The earliest reference to the condition, initially called "auditory imperception," dates back to the mid-1950s when researchers were studying children with communication disorders. The Italian researchers Bocca, Calearo, and Cassinari began developing diagnostic tests in 1954, while Kimura introduced dichotic testing in 1961 to explain the physiological basis of dichotic perception. A national conference in 1977 further stimulated research on CAPD.

CAPD can manifest in various ways: individuals may have difficulty localizing or hearing sounds in space, discriminating between multiple sounds, recognizing sound patterns, differentiating changes in speech (such as detecting sarcasm from tone changes), having sounds blocked by subsequent sounds, synthesizing sound clues meaningfully, or determining the sequence of auditory information. Diagnosis of CAPD involves systematic observation of listening behavior and/or performance on tests of auditory function, which can be conducted by audiologists, speech-language pathologists, psychologists, and others. There is no single test or tool that consistently identifies CAPD, and its cause is unknown. Many diagnostic tests present patients with multiple simultaneous auditory stimuli and ask them to differentiate specific items, such as words or numbers. Advanced tests record acoustic signals within the ear and measure responses.

In "Twelfth Night," it appears that while disguise can aid in maintaining prolonged deception, ultimately, one must discard this new persona or risk losing their true identity. Disclosing a lie can also lead to estrangement. Therefore, individuals must choose between self-preservation or maintaining relationships with others. While some may respond calmly to being deceived, others may be offended. The topic of gender role reversal in deception raises complex issues, particularly the question of why one might feel compelled to adopt the other gender's appearance. In Viola's case, it serves as a means of self-defense in a foreign land: “I’ll bring you to a captain in this town/ Where lie my maiden weeds, by whose gentle help/ I was preserved to serve this noble count…” (5.1.247-249) Her plan succeeds, but she becomes isolated from women, cutting off an important support system. Furthermore, she inadvertently attracts romantic feelings from Olivia, who mistakes her for Sebastian. “Whither, my lord? Cesario, husband, stay.” (5.1.138) Viola also grapples with suppressed romantic feelings towards Orsino: “Boy, thou hast said to me a thousand times/ Thou never shouldst love woman like to me.” (5.1.260-261) While this can be seen as progressive, modern readers might interpret Twelfth Night as a depiction of how deception can reveal hidden emotions, especially in Olivia and Orsino. Passages suggest that these characters may harbor unexpressed subconscious desires forced to the surface by Viola/Cesario's presence. For example, Olivia's love for Cesario could be due to his male appearance, or it might reveal deeper feelings towards women. However, it's likely that Olivia's attraction to Cesario is more about appearances, as Shakespeare's characters often judge based on looks. This is evident in Olivia's swift shift from loving Cesario to regarding Cesario/Viola as family rather than a romantic interest: “A sister, you are she.” (5.1.315)

German colonial rule has been widely recognized for its harshness, particularly in regard to the genocide of the Ovaherero and Nama in German South West Africa. While it's impossible to summarize an entire colonial empire so simplistically, the German colonial empire exhibited a remarkable diversity in its policies and administration, as well as in its educational approaches. Educational systems varied greatly across colonies. When the British took control of German East Africa (Tanganyika) in 1919, they found a considerable number of educated and literate Africans. German educational initiatives in Cameroon and other colonies were also commended by contemporary authors. The contrast in South West Africa (now Namibia) was stark. Unlike in East Africa, where the government established state schools and played a key role in the education of natives, in South West Africa, the task of educating natives was largely left to missionary societies that received minimal government support. The government did invest heavily in the education of Europeans, setting up a system of state schools and providing more support and regulation for missionary schools. These policies had lasting impacts on South West Africa, even after German rule. While other German colonies had significant numbers of literate and educated Africans, in South West Africa, “the overwhelming majority of the population remained untouched, uneducated, and illiterate.” Numerous social, political, and economic factors contributed to this divergent experience in South West Africa. This paper aims to broaden the discussion by identifying these factors and focusing on new research on the attitudes of settlers and colonial authorities toward native Africans.

There is a substantial body of literature about education in the German colonial empire, much of it in German and written either during or shortly after the colonial era. Earlier works mainly aimed to describe the educational systems in these colonies, while later works, often in English, expanded the discourse through comparative studies and in-depth analyses. These studies highlighted the differences in educational systems across colonies. The most notable work addressing this topic is Cohen's study of education in South West Africa and East Africa. Cohen compares the educational systems of the two colonies and discusses the factors accounting for their differences. According to Cohen, the large settler population in South West Africa explains many of the unique aspects of its educational system.

Compared to Germany’s other colonial territories, South West Africa had a moderately temperate climate, although much of it is covered by arid desert. This climate was reflected in a European population that was relatively hospitable, with nearly 15,000 whites in South West Africa by 1913, compared to around 5,336 in the colony with the next largest settler population, East Africa.

The categorization of Popular Music has expanded significantly over the past century, encompassing numerous genres that are hard to enumerate exhaustively. This complexity is further compounded by the fact that many of these genres, such as rap, rock, country, jazz, and folk, have spawned numerous sub-genres and sub-sub-genres. In particular, the sub-genre of Heavy Metal rock has emerged as one of the most diverse and expressive genres in Popular Music over the last 40 years. Its expressiveness stems from its broad emotional range, which often leans towards darker hues. Additionally, the genre's flexibility has led to the creation of numerous sub-genres and sub-sub-genres, creating a continuous chain of evolution. Today, the heavy metal scene is so fragmented that it's challenging to define what constitutes heavy metal, as it has absorbed themes from various other genres. To grasp the contemporary metal music scene, one must first understand the metal movement's origins and its nature as a movement rather than just a genre.

Heavy metal, in many respects, is defined by its darkness. It can be seen as "music with more" — more bass, more volume, more aggression, and more theatricality. It emphasizes instrumental prowess, with musicians demonstrating their proficiency. Moreover, metal has a strong association with drug use, particularly psychedelic drugs in the 1970s, which allowed musicians to explore more extreme, otherworldly sounds. This genre possesses dark, visceral qualities, which was unusual for popular music at the time, as it strayed from more upbeat themes. Later generations of metal musicians have drawn inspiration from these dark, visceral qualities, which are reminiscent of the Romantic Era. Lyrics like those from "Helter Skelter" by The Beatles exemplify this darkness and are considered one of the early Heavy Metal songs. It was a response to a Rolling Stones song and marked The Beatles' attempt to match the Stones' heavier, darker sound on their album "The White Album".

Several years before Surrealist artists began creating their dream-like works, Henri Rousseau was already crafting his own dreams, both literally and metaphorically. "The Dream," a 1910 painting by the renowned Post-Impressionist artist, showcases not only a woman enchanted by the wonders of a dream landscape but also Rousseau's personal dreams and ambitions as an artist. Throughout his career, Rousseau yearned for recognition, acceptance, and admiration from fellow artists and art enthusiasts, yet he faced a challenging internal conflict: to conform to or imitate established painting styles to gain acceptance in the critical art world or to retain his creative independence and uniqueness. "The Dream" embodies Rousseau's lifelong internal struggle. Prior to examining "The Dream" through this lens, one should be familiar with Rousseau's biography. Born on May 21, 1844, in Laval, northwest France, Rousseau's father ran a successful tinsmith and hardware business. He lacked formal art training but worked as a gabelou (employee of the municipal toll service) until age forty, earning the nickname douanier (customs inspector). After the deaths of his wife and infant children, Rousseau turned to painting for solace and new beginnings. Unlike his contemporaries, Rousseau was a folk painter, echoing the hopes and dreams of the common people. Understanding Rousseau's desire for artistic acceptance is not surprising given his lack of formal training, late start, and the presence of many esteemed artists working concurrently. While he and Matisse were rivals in the art world, they differed in painting styles, subjects, and motivations. According to Jan Gordon in "Modern French Painters," Matisse feared painting tritely, whereas Rousseau aimed to create something conventional enough to gain admission into the Artiste Français.

Many prominent thinkers have proposed a deep connection between ethics and aesthetics, and truth and beauty. I contend that this connection has a fundamental reason. John Keats, in his "Ode on a Grecian Urn," asserts that "Beauty is truth, truth beauty - That is all / Ye know on earth, and all ye need to know." While much of our knowledge comes from education or experience, we intuitively appreciate ethics and aesthetics without formal teaching. Both ethics and aesthetics seek to describe rather than prescribe. Our analyses of morality and beauty are primarily attempts to explain the reasons behind something's beauty or morality, not to dictate rules for creating good art or moral behavior. Critiquing art or morals can't fully capture their essence. For instance, discussing the worth of Da Vinci's Mona Lisa may involve aspects like foreground, background, contrast, or cultural context, but these don't explain why it's good art. Often, when discussing a favorite piece of art or literature, we hear phrases like, "There's just something about it" before delving into more complex explanations. Both art and morality cannot be fully reduced to descriptions of their qualities, as there's always a transcendent element, as Flannery O'Connor and Wittgenstein suggest. I believe this shared transcendent nature binds ethics and aesthetics together. I posit that we experience both morality and art most potently in a way that's ineffable, or beyond explanation, at a noumenal level. This is especially true for literature, which uniquely combines moral quality with its aesthetic appeal, as McKean observes.

Germany today is recognized as a powerful and unified nation, with a distinctive culture that varies from the alpine region of Munich to the Baltic Sea city of Kiel, and from Cologne along the Rhine River to the central region and the Saxon city of Dresden on the Elbe. This cultural diversity is not surprising given that Germany has evolved from a mix of different tribes and sources. The land of Germania, the ancestral home of the Germans, has an uncertain origin. Some scholars suggest it comes from the Germanic tribe called the Tungrians, who were previously known as Germans before crossing the Rhine and fighting against Gallic forces, as noted by Tacitus in AD 98. Others propose that the name derives from the German weapon, the ger, or from the Old Irish word "garim" meaning "to shout," indicating the Germans' loud nature. The early Roman historian Tacitus, in his writings, argued that the Germans were indigenous and had not mixed with other races through immigration or contact. He described Germany as a place with harsh conditions, which might not attract immigrants from more hospitable climates like Asia, Africa, or Italy. The Romans primarily traded with the Germanic tribes, with occasional military campaigns, but mostly returned home to their empire. As Germanic tribes began appearing in the first century, they lived on the Roman Empire's borders, trading their goods and skills within the Roman army.

I gazed down, my mind empty, observing the scene before me. Impassively, silently, with a practiced detachment that analyzed the picture without connecting to any abstract understanding, my mind processed the image. Thoughts flickered through my mind, but they were ephemeral and fleeting, like a quick and smooth flow of consciousness. I couldn't relate to the picture as an artist would, but rather experienced it as a passive observer. I had always wanted to draw, and I had once bought a book called "The New Drawing on the Right Side of the Brain" which taught everything from understanding a pencil to how the brain interprets lines. One technique it taught was to frame a square around a picture to simplify it, turning a complex scene into a manageable one. Looking at the bowl of fruit in front of me, I couldn't mentally frame the picture. I was too overwhelmed, too awestruck to process it. I was standing at the beginning of what could be my artistic journey, my "Work in Brown." My hand touched the brush, muscles tensed and relaxed as I moved it through space, giving form to my thoughts. Water swirled smoothly, clear and clean. Small bits of matter broke away, floating away. Flush after flush, I struggled to dislodge the stubborn brown package. Frustrated, I gripped the mop and began to wrap it around my hand like a glove. Standing tall, I slowly dipped my hand into the bowl, like a mother reaching into an oven for the Thanksgiving turkey...

Teenagers are dying in car accidents at an alarming rate due to a combination of factors. The National Institutes of Health point out that a key issue is the immaturity of the teenage brain, which is not yet fully capable of handling the hazards of driving. Lack of experience also plays a significant role, leading to more crashes, rollovers, speeding incidents, and off-road accidents. Teenagers are particularly at risk when they drive with peers, as studies have shown a correlation between the number of passengers and the frequency of traffic accidents.

Several states have tried to enhance teen driver safety by implementing provisional licenses that restrict driving hours and forbid minors as passengers. However, these measures are considered temporary solutions. The underlying problem is that, statistically, young drivers are not equipped to handle the risks and responsibilities that come with driving. Psychology research suggests that even at 18, teens might not be mature enough to drive safely. The risk-taking tendency among teens under 19-20 years old is another concern. By 2010, the Baby Boomer generation's children will be old enough to drive, adding millions of new teen drivers to the roads.

A reasonable solution would involve schools continuing to offer driver's education classes but prohibiting anyone under 18 from driving a vehicle. Provisional permits could still be issued before granting a full driver's license, along with a certain number of required driving practice hours. These hours could be based on current state requirements, such as California's 6 hours of behind-the-wheel training and 50 hours of practice with an adult. Nationwide legislation would be a practical and effective way to protect teen drivers across the country, as the problem affects all states.

Upon perusing the Library of Congress's collection of early Edison films, I chose to watch all the trick films, numbering fifteen from 1895 to 1901. These films employ creative editing to create illusions. My analysis primarily focused on detailing the poetics of most trick films and identifying unique characteristics in a few of the later ones. Generally, these films are confined to a set, staged within a frontal proscenium, with no camera movement, using long and medium shots, and adhering to the one-shot-per-film rule. However, a few films from the early 20th century challenge these norms by incorporating elements like multiple shots.

One common feature among trick films is their indoor setting, framed within a frontal proscenium. The camera remains stationary, not moving to track figures or objects. This style was prevalent in early films and drew inspiration from theatre and vaudeville. One limitation is that figures in trick films usually move side-to-side, without moving towards or away from the camera. For instance, in Uncle Josh in a Spooky Hotel (1900), actors enter from the right and move back and forth horizontally, without the camera following them out of frame.

This frontal proscenium setup leads to long and, less frequently, medium shots, with close-ups never occurring in any Edison trick film. This technique, like the theatre and vaudeville tradition, allows the audience to see the entire performance at once, framed by the stage borders. Actors do not move towards the camera, so close-ups are absent.

Most early trick films follow the rule that one conceptual shot equates to one film, restricting their length to about a minute or less. This also limits their dramatic or narrative potential, with most focusing on simple vaudeville-style tricks like magic and disappearing acts. However, a single conceptual shot in the viewer's eyes may not correspond to a single physical shot. For instance, in The Execution of Mary, Queen of Scots (1895), a closer look reveals the moment where the physical shot with Mary's severed "head" starts, despite the film being conceptually one shot to the viewer.

John Taylor from Caroline was an early and passionate advocate for the Republican cause. Primarily an agriculturalist, his background and brief political career shaped him into a staunch defender of personal liberties and government oversight. His commitment to agrarianism informed his views on governance, including issues of sovereignty, constitutionalism, and the judiciary. Taylor believed that the United States had a unique opportunity to establish a perfect system due to the lack of traditional barriers, allowing for self-government. He held that natural rights are interconnected and should be beyond government control to maintain their full value. He contended that in a civilized society, power should not rest with the strongest or most cunning. Taylor advocated for a government that accounts for the inherent goodness and evil in humans, adhering to a dualistic morality. He viewed good principles as those that safeguard property, enhance agriculture, and curb capitalism. He believed that self-interest, while natural in humans, becomes harmful when it leads to societal exploitation. He argued for a limited federal government, with no powers beyond those explicitly stated in the Constitution, to avoid despotism and corruption. He also considered the Declaration of Independence the true foundation of the United States, as it more clearly defines the country as a union of sovereign states rather than a single nation.

In Figure 17, we noticed a sharp decrease in commuter log submissions in the third month of the project. The reason behind this drop is unclear, but it could be attributed to the start of winter in New England, which often leads to fewer people commuting by bicycle or on foot. Additionally, December is typically a busy time for students and faculty, as it marks the end of the fall semester and the holiday season. This could have caused the commuter log to be overlooked. Furthermore, the month-long break for students and faculty due to the holiday season and the resumption of classes in late January might also explain the low number of submissions. It's possible that the project experienced an initial surge in enthusiasm that naturally declined. To counteract this trend, we introduced the Carpool Challenge Week in March, which led to an increase in log submissions. However, maintaining project momentum was challenging due to both natural decreases in engagement and the impact of holiday and semester breaks. Another obstacle was the cultural preference for driving cars, so offering incentives for alternative commuting modes was crucial. We provided various prizes, such as gift certificates to local businesses and even larger prizes like bicycles or hybrid/electric cars. The value of the prizes could have been increased over time to potentially boost participation even more.

An ETF (exchange-traded fund) is a type of security that was developed to mirror an index, a commodity, or a collection of assets similar to an index fund, but it trades more flexibly like a stock on an exchange. ETFs offer the diversification of index funds and the perks of individual stock ownership, such as the ability to short sell, use margin, and buy as few as one share per trade. Despite these advantages, ETFs typically have lower expense ratios than mutual funds. However, they do come with a trade-off: you have to pay a commission for each ETF trade, just like you would for a stock. Additionally, ETFs are known for their wide range of available funds. It's beneficial for investors to assess whether the claimed benefits, such as diversification, actually exist and to what degree. For this analysis, we will examine the IHF ETF and its top 10 holdings, which account for 63.58% of the total assets, to evaluate if owning a single ETF could provide benefits similar to owning a diversified portfolio of the top 10 stocks, and if there are configurations that offer better risk-return ratios. To streamline our analysis, we'll focus on the top 10 holdings. The table below lists these holdings and their respective percentages of total assets.

To gauge how well these top 10 stocks represent the IHF ETF, we will calculate their contributions to a portfolio's Beta and Return, assuming the portfolio consists of these 10 stocks in the same proportions as the ETF's holdings. The calculations for Beta and return are shown in the chart below.

From this chart, it's clear that a portfolio of just the top 10 holdings would yield a 6.11% higher return than the ETF, an increase of 16%. Additionally, the Beta of the top 10 holdings is lower by 0.12 than that of the entire ETF. Based on these results, a portfolio of the top 10 holdings could potentially offer a higher return with a lower risk (Beta). However, statistical differences between the two portfolios remain uncertain.

To further evaluate the statistical differences between the two portfolios, we will calculate the standard deviation of each of the top 10 stocks and normalize it to 100% to compare their accumulated standard deviation against that of the IHF ETF.

"Dream-Land" is one of Edgar Allan Poe's self-proclaimed best poems. In this work, Poe employs the term "Thulé" in lines 6 and 56, which Mabbott links to Virgil. Virgil used the term to refer to an island north of Britain, seen by the Greeks as the farthest known world. While Virgil indeed used the term, another more recent source may have influenced Poe. Poe was particularly interested in German authors.

The quote is notable for demonstrating Poe's familiarity with Goethe's writing. Karl J. Arndt, in "Poe's Politian and Goethe's Mignon," points out the similarities between Poe's and Goethe's poems, concluding that Poe was likely imitating Goethe.

The Oxford Companion to English Literature describes Goethe as a renowned writer of the poetic drama "Faust," published in two parts, the first in 1808 and the second in 1832, the year of Goethe's death. In the second part of Faust, there's a short poem called "The King of Thulé," about a king who loses his wife after receiving a goblet from her. Driven by grief to drink, he eventually decides to end his life and throw the goblet into the sea. The king's fate echoes the desolation and grief found in "Dream-Land."

Poe mentions Thule twice in his works, including "The Pit and the Pendulum." In "Dream-Land," he uses the term twice as bookends for the poem. "The King of Thulé" and "Dream-Land" can be seen as companion pieces. In "Dream-Land," the speaker describes the landscape of Thulé as dark and lonely, haunted by dead friends, and devoid of color—a representation of Poe's own feelings of loss and despair over drinking. The poem reads as if the speaker has stepped into Goethe's world.

Goethe was a significant author whose works Poe would have known, possibly due to his admiration for Tennyson. When asked about Tennyson, Poe expressed his admiration. Additionally, Poe would have been exposed to Goethe's work through various reproductions following the original publications.

According to California law, could a customer injured by falling on an applesauce spill in a grocery store win punitive damages by proving the store manager acted maliciously, knowing the spill was dangerous but not addressing it for half an hour to finish his dinner?

A judge is unlikely to dismiss Jennifer Palmer's claim for punitive damages outright. To win such damages, she must show the store manager's actions were deliberate and showed a disregard for the risk of harm, as well as that the actions were particularly egregious. Palmer can argue that the manager should have cleaned the spill promptly to prevent further injuries, given that multiple customers had previously slipped and fallen due to spills. While her argument that the manager's inaction was despicable may not be overwhelmingly convincing, it is still reasonable given that six slip-and-fall incidents had occurred in the store in 2009, and the manager did not take sufficient action to ensure customer safety.

On October 13, 2009, at 5:00 pm, an employee named Rich Wayne informed his manager, Paul Martin, about an applesauce spill in an aisle. Martin responded that he was on his dinner break and couldn't deal with the issue. At 5:15 pm, another employee, Mary J. Haddigan, also reported the spill to Martin, who responded similarly. At 5:30 pm, Palmer slipped and fell on the spill, sustaining a serious back injury. Before Palmer's accident, five other slip-and-fall incidents had been reported at D&D's in 2009. Palmer is now suing D&D for both compensatory and punitive damages, and we are considering whether to file a summary judgment motion against the punitive damages claim.

In California, a plaintiff can obtain punitive damages for a non-contractual breach if the defendant acted with "oppression, fraud, or malice." Cal. Civ. Code, § 3294(a) (Lexis 2010). The statute defines malice as conduct that either intended to cause harm or, if there was no such intent, was "despicable" and was done with a "willful and conscious disregard of the rights or safety of others." Id. at § (c)(1). Courts have deemed conduct malicious when the defendant was aware of the probable dangerous consequences of their actions and willfully failed to avoid them. Taylor v. Super. Ct. of Los Angeles Co., 598 P. 2d 853, 856 (Cal. 1979).

Around four years ago, I took an Islam class at CBC. Our class frequently debated whether Islam is a hostile religion, and that question seems more pertinent now than ever. Reflecting on events since 9/11, I've noticed a shift in the U.S. media's portrayal of Islam and extremists, from hostility to extreme tolerance. In 2001, it's unlikely we would have seen a presidential candidate like Barack Obama, with an evident Muslim background in his family. The Prophet Muhammad's biography intrigues me because it seems to conflict with the historical accounts of his personality. Traditionally, I believed Muhammad forced converts to Islam through conquest, but the biography portrays him as a humble prophet misunderstood by others, who one by one came to acknowledge his teachings. The similarities between Jesus' ministry and Muhammad's miracles, such as multiplying mutton and milk to feed forty men, suggest the writers aimed to depict Muhammad as a prophet who didn't need to prove his credentials but simply lived his truth. This approach, I argue, diminishes Jesus' life and miracles. Moreover, many stories in the biography seem to aim to provide 'witnesses' or personal conversions to Islam, often based on hearsay. These accounts, with their third-party perspectives, feel less credible and more suspicious to me. Lastly, I find the biography's portrayal of Muhammad as a godly, humble, wise, and gentle man misleading, as historical records show otherwise. I wonder if modern Muslims are aware of the true history behind Muhammad's rise to power.

After Jesus' passing, his teachings and beliefs were quickly overshadowed in the evolution of Christian thought. Over time, Christianity diverged increasingly from its original roots. Present-day society exhibits a heightened awareness and progressive tendencies, though traditionalists may linger and oppose new ideas. Christian historians will likely deepen their understanding of the faith, seeking to distinguish later additions from Jesus' original intentions. Eventually, a strong movement will emerge to strip away these additions, reverting Christianity to its initial form. As this trend spreads in the United States and Europe, masses may return to worshipping as they did during Jesus' time, guided by his ideas alone. Although this could lead to increased uniformity within Christianity, the institutional church will remain strong. Throughout history, we've seen reversals, such as when Christianity went from being persecuted by the Roman Empire to becoming its dominant religion. The impending reversion in Christianity will follow this pattern, simplifying the faith and reducing its diversity. This transformation will be aided by interpreting Jesus' words metaphorically rather than literally. Looking back through history, Judaism was the precursor to Christianity, centered around monotheism, divine revelation, and the authority of the Hebrew scriptures before the Romans controlled Jerusalem in 63 B.C.E. Jews were diverse, categorized into groups like Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, and Zealots, along with a majority of common people.

I contend that "The Jungle" by Upton Sinclair illustrates the inherent greed and self-interest of human nature. Individuals prioritize their own well-being and success, disregarding those beneath them. This theme is evident in the factory owners and managers, whose sole aim is to expand their empires, without regard for the harm caused by their actions. Sinclair's description of the factories "a line of buildings stood clear-cut and black against the sky, with great chimneys pouring out rivers of smoke" underscores the environmental damage they inflict. The owners' apathy towards the suffering of people and animals, whether from pollution or harsh working conditions, is apparent. They prioritize profits over worker safety, as seen in their exploitative labor practices and absence of compensation for layoffs. Laws and regulations during that time offered little protection, allowing managers and owners to exploit their employees in substandard conditions. Workers were essentially trapped in this system, with no recourse or assistance, and were often forced to work to the point of death. Unions, while formed to help, often compounded the workers' misery by enriching themselves. Sinclair's comparison of workers to slaves highlights their desperate plight, unable to escape the brutal system that left them "hanging always on the verge of starvation, dependent for opportunities of life upon the whim of men as brutal and unscrupulous as the old-time slave drivers"

Many authors employ various methods to evoke specific emotions or perspectives in their readers. F. Scott Fitzgerald, in his novel "The Great Gatsby," employs a number of these techniques with varying degrees of effectiveness. One approach he uses is to pair adjectives and nouns in unusual combinations to create a particular atmosphere. Additionally, he assigns symbolic significance to colors and reuses these symbols to reinforce his narrative. In "The Great Gatsby," Fitzgerald attributes specific meanings to colors like white/gray and red/pink, which he then employs to evoke particular sensations around key subjects.

Fitzgerald's association of white/gray with uniformity is evident in his use of these colors throughout the novel. White is often associated with higher social status and elegance, while gray signifies age and faded appearances. This is first established at the novel's outset with frequent mentions of white and gray. Characters such as Daisy and Jordan are consistently described as "in white," and even minor characters like Nick, Tom, and Catherine are depicted in white attire. Furthermore, Fitzgerald employs these colors to describe mundane subjects, enhancing their significance. For instance, Nick travels "down the white chasms of lower New York," and the names of partygoers are "gray names." Even simple objects and settings, like apartment houses and cars, are described in terms of white and gray, reinforcing their symbolism.

After establishing the meanings of white/gray, Fitzgerald uses them to convey a sense of uniformity or insignificance. This technique begins with Daisy, who is first described as "dressed in white" in a "little white roadster." This use of white diminishes her character status, making her seem more like a uniform addition, an object of Gatsby's desire. Fitzgerald continues to use this technique with Daisy, such as describing her "gray haze of fur collar" and her outfit as "white" before her encounter with Tom and Gatsby.

San Diego County is exceptionally fertile due to its mild and sunny climate. Common crops include tomatoes, citrus fruits, leafy greens, squash, broccoli, herbs, tree fruits such as peaches and lemons, berries, honey, and peppers. There is a strong demand for organic community supported agriculture (CSA) in the San Diego region, with many local organizations boasting long waiting lists for their services. Organic eggs and milk are also popular purchases. Many organic farms offer tours of their operations and access to recreational activities like hiking and birdwatching. This setup allows landowners to benefit from government programs while enhancing habitat, promoting recreational use, and creating opportunities for farm tours and educational programs.

Organic farming typically offers greater biodiversity in plants and wildlife due to the absence of chemicals. However, it can be more labor-intensive and costly than conventional farming, as it requires intensive management to control pests and weeds and maintain soil fertility without chemicals. Additionally, organic farms may experience higher losses and lack the economies of scale enjoyed by larger operations. Certain practices beneficial to wildlife, like planting cover crops, strategic grazing rotation, and invasive species removal, also require more labor. Therefore, landowners in this scenario might seek financial assistance or expertise to balance profit and habitat quality.

The land in question is a 160-acre parcel near Potrero, in unincorporated San Diego County, bordering the Cleveland National Forest. This land includes chaparral, nonnative Mediterranean grassland, and oak woodland, and is part of the East County Southern Foothills ecoregion in the San Diego Multiple Species Conservation Plan. The plan currently recognizes over a hundred species of plants and animals, with many being endangered, such as the Stephens' kangaroo rat, mountain yellow-legged frog, several butterfly species, and the California gnatcatcher, and others are declining and may soon be listed as endangered, like burrowing owls.

This land has a rich history of habitation by Native Americans for centuries and was later settled by cattle ranchers and cordwood sellers in the late 1800s. It was part of an original homestead and likely used for grazing and wood production for many years. After researching available government programs, a model organic farm in the same area was identified as a potential example of what could be achieved with this land.

Culture is a crucial factor in any negotiation. It can be understood as much by its absence as by its presence and significance. Culture is not uniform or isolated. Blanket statements like "all Russians are stubborn" or "all Japanese are accommodating" are too simplistic. While it's helpful to grasp the general traits of a culture, a skilled negotiator should focus on how the culture's attitudes affect the negotiation process. When encountering a foreign culture, it's natural to relate it to one's own culture, leading to inevitable comparisons. Understanding a foreign culture or mindset may involve delving into its history, understanding its biases, and accepting it for what it is, rather than trying to change it. This is especially important if you're in a weaker bargaining position or in "away" territory. Cultural nuances extend beyond national borders, as individual companies often have their own distinct cultures, influencing factors like work hours, communication styles, and hiring practices. Some companies may encourage or restrict employee philanthropy. Even cultures that appear uniform can have deep layers. Understanding a culture's values, which provide its "why," is equally important. For instance, if a culture values saving face or communal harmony, a negotiator will refrain from public humiliation. Similarly, a negotiator from a culture that values aggressive bargaining will not relent easily. Before negotiation, it's beneficial to learn about one's opponent's personal background to enhance the process.

The statement "There is no God" was supposedly made by a fool, as written in Psalm 14 of the Christian Bible, and is the starting point for St. Anselm's argument about God's existence. This belief is shared by another author we'll discuss, Thomas Aquinas. Since both are defending the same idea, and we're to compare their arguments, we'll assume they both believe in the Bible's God for simplicity's sake. Assuming any other god wouldn't allow a fair comparison, as their arguments are specific to this concept. However, both arguments fall short of providing a comprehensive basis for believing in God. To illustrate this, let's first look at St. Anselm's main argument. He proposes that we find truth about God within our own understanding. He argues that because we can't imagine God's non-existence, we can thereby prove his existence. This idea, though complex, suggests that the proof for God lies within our own minds, not requiring external evidence. This is often referred to as faith in Christian texts. In contrast, St. Thomas Aquinas advocates for proving God's existence through reason and empirical evidence alone, without needing faith. His five logical arguments, including change, causation, contingency, degrees of excellence, and harmony, suggest that God's existence can be deduced from logic.

Around the 5th or 6th century BCE, a future Buddha was born. He left the worldly life, achieved enlightenment, and his teachings eventually led to the formation of Buddhism, with Theravada Buddhism being the most traditional branch. This religion is now about 2500 years old and has evolved significantly since Buddha's time, evident in practices like the annual water-cutting ceremony in Sri Lanka, where monks and laypeople participate despite Buddha not teaching such rituals. These changes span from superficial traditions to the religion's core beliefs. Theravada Buddhism, both from the monastic and lay perspectives, has had to adapt its doctrines over time due to both external and internal influences, both friendly and hostile.

Throughout this discussion, several terms will be used. Internal forces are those originating from within the Buddhist community, while external forces come from non-Buddhists. Hostile forces harm or intend to harm Buddhism, while benign forces do not wish to harm the community but may inadvertently do so. These terms will be frequently used.

First, let's explore the core of Theravada Buddhism. Buddhists find refuge in the Three Jewels: the Buddha, the Dhamma, and the Sangha. The Dhamma includes the Tripitaka, three collections of texts: the Sutta Pitaka (containing Suttas), the Vinaya Pitaka (disciplinary rules), and the Abhidhamma Pitaka (metaphysical concepts like Anatta, Dukkha, and Anicca). Understanding these concepts helps one break the cycle of Sansara (death and rebirth), along with its components: lobha (desire), dosa (hatred), and moha (delusion). When one becomes enlightened, these cease. The Vinaya Pitaka outlines rules for laypeople (five precepts) and monks (many more). Fundamental to Buddhism is the Four Noble Truths: life is suffering (Dukkha), attachment causes suffering, suffering can be overcome, and there is a way to achieve this.

America and Mexico once had a long-standing rivalry that lasted from 1836 to 1893, with the Mexican-American War of 1846-1848 serving as the peak of their conflict. Other disputes also occurred between the two nations, with the rivalry subsiding just before World War I. The animosity began due to disagreements over religion, culture, and economic interests, not unlike many border-sharing nations. David M. Pletcher (1977) notes that only Mexico and Cuba posed long-term challenges to U.S. diplomacy due to their proximity and rivalry. Religious tensions, rooted in historic distrust between the English and Spanish, were a significant obstacle to friendly relations. Diehl and Goerts (2000) enumerate 17 disputes, mainly involving territorial issues caused by raids and outlaw activities across the border. Schmitt (1974) attributes the easing of the rivalry to Mexico's growing dependence on the U.S. and the shift in American aims from territorial expansion to economic intervention in Mexico in the late 19th century.

Fifteen years ago, I was unexpectedly struck by a previously unknown illness that left me disabled. At the time, I was a nurse, having chosen this career to ensure safety and security, driven by my childhood experiences and the reassuring mantra that "You'll always be able to find work; people will always get sick." Even though my dream was to become a scientist or journalist, I chose nursing. Yet, here I am, at 46 years old, single, and unable to work.
